My story about skiing in Caucasus Mountains in Georgia is live today on @natgeo! I am thrilled to finally share this series that I worked on last year. Traveling to Ushguli, which is protected by UNESCO, has been on my bucket list for a long time, and it's one of those timeless places you can't help but return to. Huge thanks to the amazing assistance of @shako_margiani and @maticek. 

Ushguli is considered the highest permanently inhabited point in Europe. According to the publicist Besarion Nizharadze, the name Ushguli, as a toponym, originates from 'fearless heart'. Thanks for great editing to photo editor @maurafriedman @natgeo. 

Please follow the link in my profile to read the story on @natgeo. I'll be sharing more from this trip in the coming days, so stay tuned.
#natgeo #skitouring #georgia #svaneti #ushguli #leica #leicaSL

The Western Balkans region is home to some of Europeâ€™s last free-flowing rivers. There is a growing movement of people who are fighting to protect these unique ecosystems for generations to come. We were given the task to produce 8 short films about river champions and guardians, from scientists to locals who are trying to protect rivers in the Balkans.

#riverchampions #thenatureconservancy #unitedforrivers #tentfilm

I am honored to serve as a nominator for the LOBA 2024 once again. The Leica Oskar Barnack Award is one of the most important photography awards, and I will never forget when I received this  recognition in 2013. We are actively seeking bodies of work centered around the theme of the relationship between humans and their environment.

If you believe you have a compelling and relevant series, please feel free to send me an email at ciril@tentfilm.com, including your work and an artistic statement. Additionally, you are welcome to tag someone whom you believe deserves this recognition. 

Attached are some photos from my LOBA-winning series 'Waiting to Move,' captured during my expedition to Shishmaref, Sarichef Island, Alaska. The purpose of this journey was to document the effects of climate change on the lives of the InÌƒupiat people.

The Ford GT90 Concept Car 

Unveiled in 1995 to celebrate Ford's 90th anniversary and honor the iconic GT40, the Ford GT90 concept car was a bold statement of automotive innovation. It housed a potent quad-turbocharged 6.0-liter V12 engine generating up to 720 horsepower. 

It included advanced features like carbon fiber construction, traction control, and active suspension, the GT90 boasted impressive performance figures, reportedly hitting a top speed of 253 mph (407 km/h) and achieving 0-60 mph in just 3.1 seconds. Despite its acclaim, the GT90 never saw production, serving as a testament to Ford's boundary-pushing engineering and design capabilities.

Rumor has it that only one GT90 Concept Car was ever made, and it currently resides at the Hajek Motorsports Museum in Ames, Oklahoma.

One of the most exciting shoots I did last year was working with the @eastafricanreptiles & Taylor Ashe Antivenom center in Watamu, Kenya to photograph spitting cobras. This particular snake is a Red Spitting Cobra (Naja pallida). Photographing these snakes is a challenge because they are not only highly venomous but they can be very aggressive/defensive as well. I had to wear a full face shield, which allowed me to avoid getting any of the venom they spit in my eyes, nose or ears.

Snakes are sadly often misunderstood and killed on sight no matter the circumstance, which is horrible because they are such a vital part of the eco systems we all live in. Organizations like East Africa Reptile's focus much of their attention not only on education and safety,  but in helping to safely remove snakes from people's homes and properties around Kenya, further increasing their chances of survival.

Sony a7R V w/ 90mm f/2.8 Macro Lens + 2 @godox_global V860 III OCF Units

This is one of the most unique looking frogs you can find in Costa Rica, known as the Coronated Tree Frog. It's name comes from the fact that at certain angles, it looks as if it is wearing a crown. It is one of many different species of frogs and snakes that we look for during my Costa Rica wildlife workshops I run each January.

Last September I found myself wandering around the deserts of Dubai in search of the Horned Arabian Viper. Unfortunately for me, it was the wrong time of year as they tend to love the hot desert nights. We did however find a number of these Saw Scaled Vipers (Echis Carinatus). These beautiful snakes are easily the most deadly snake in the UAE, accounting for more snake bites per year than all other snakes combined. They can be aggressive, have a quick strike and a very powerful venom.

Thanks to @wildlifewithnitin for showing me around! Can't wait for the next adventure!

Climbing brings us together.  Once you challenge yourself with gravity and share this experience with your friends something changes. It's the international language of belaying and spotting. It's the same everywhere. You have to trust someone to achieve your goals. 

@memphisroxclimbing has been a flywheel for the good that climbing brings. Built in the shell of a supermarket with a state of the facility, Rox is bringing gym climbing and outdoor experiences to South Memphis.

With a pay as one can model, the gym is open to everyone. Climbing as I was introduced to it was free. The cliffs were at  end of the road and my dad and his buddies had the gear and knowledge. I still recall the moment when climbing and being outdoors latched on. It's that same emotion that we see with the people we welcome to the crag, mountain and gym. Let's keep that going! 

The freedom that climbing brings comes at a cost. The facility and staff are monthly obligations. In business, as in climbing, the unexpected happens. In this case a burst water pipe needs immediate attention. To keep Rox a safe place (it's a polling station, health care facility and restaurant) the security team needs immediate funding. Going without costs the program more. 

Rox has been a part of my life for the past six years. I've made new friends, shared backcountry experience & knowledge while climbing outdoors and learned from each other on how to address the challenges of race in the United States. 

If you believe in the mission of @memphisroxclimbing please consider a donation. It will be put to good use. If you have the chance to visit Memphis, stop by the gym. You'll find family by the time you have warmed up.

#thankyou

The @khumbuclimbingcenter begins with a Puja ceremony. The students, instructors and volunteers hike to the lower Khumbila ice flows and share a meaningful start to the course. Aou Lama has been part of this tradition for 14 years. 
Once the ceremony concludes we toss toasted barley in the sky for long life. We then share the pemar (barley cake cone) and Losar biscuits. Once the goodness is lined out we begin climbing.

Kyle Allen Rott 1987 - 2023 
On  November  25th we lost Kyle in a fall in Hyalite Canyon, Montana. My heart goes out to his mother and sister and the South Dakota family of this fine man.  For his friends the loss is immediate. The years of being together,  weaving the fabric of friendship through shared experiences are gone.

Kyle was a climber. Once he realized that the pursuit of gravity was his life's calling,  he lived with a singular purpose. "Let's go climb."

As someone close to Kyle, his "uncle" by age and knowing him with our family, his loss is another weight on the scale of "is it worth it".

Many of my close friends are introverts. In school we found each other and climbing self selected us. Kyle and I climbed together for 15 years - most of the time hiking the folds of Southwest Montana looking for the cliffs and drips that sustain us. In between climbs he helped out by housesitting for the climbing community. For those of that trusted Kyle without houses and animals - you know how conscientious he was.  Kyle's humble approach to life - not entertaining anything superfluous - was reflected by living in his truck.  Which made housesitting a good balance. 

While Kyle was quiet and shy in a room of his peers, there was this friendly side that Kyle shared with people in life. More than once he would carefully explain the gadgets needed to climb to curious people on the trail. This translated well to the guiding he did with Montana Alpine Guides and the Mountain School in Yosemite. 

At our service for Kyle we wrote in a small book for his mother and family. His worldly possessions, kept tidy in a Livingston storage locker, spread out over a picnic table, passed to his friends. They will cherish his memory and then ply the seas of gravity, risking it all for the moment. For his age peers, dealing with non sequential death, many for the first time, left adrift questioning and bonding closer with those that stand. I was there. And now 30 years later as an elder, with culpability and responsibility.

We love you Kyle for energy you brought to our climbing adventures. 

We love you for the reminder to live calm. 

Photos @petetapley

The curb weight of the Porsche 356, the first Porsche automobile, was 1700 â€“ 2,296 lbs. The weight of the Porsche name is much heavier. Ferdinand â€˜Ferdiâ€™ Porsche, an architect by trade and the great grandson of the companyâ€™s founder Prof. Ferdinand Porsche, is now adding his fingerprint to the familyâ€™s rich motor-sports legacy.

At 30 yrs old, Ferdi defies all the seriousness and pomp of racing cars. Heâ€™s affable, warm, and almost boyish in his excitement. To put it bluntly, heâ€™s â€˜coolâ€™ without effort, working hard to invite the next generation into the motorsports world.

 On February 24, Ferdiâ€™s F.A.T. International held its first ice race in Zell am See, Austria, and has followed it up in Aspen, Colorado. Over the past two days on an icy track in Carbondale, the race has included models from the @aetherapparel Half11 (half Porsche, half F1) to the Rivian R1T, to a host of various Mobil 1 cars tearing around corners, over-steering, under-steering, and generally bringing joy as they spit rooster tails of snow from their tires. 

I watch as an enthusiast warm his hands in the exhaust of a loud engine. He brings them to his nose, closes his eyes and inhales deeply, letting his senses coalesce into something whole and visceral. Ferdi sits in his car nearby grinning. Itâ€™s an expression of sincere, palpable joy. As an arm drops, he accelerates onto the track. In a burst of exhaust, something old becomes new again. Itâ€™s a Herculean task and these are enormous shoes to fill, but Ferdi seems to be carrying the weight of legacy effortlessly.

Words by Ben Ayers @jetbutterflies // In the wide desert of Upper Mustang, the road planes along canyon walls and dry mountainsides dotted with hundreds of unspeakably ancient human-made caves. The light plays a slow game of chase with the shadows cast by the highest mountains on the planet, now behind us. We sweep the corners wide, drawn to cliff-edges teetering above the braided Kali Gandaki River below. We donâ€™t know where to look â€“ the road, the layers of tortured mountains, or the sand-castle parapets of rock and mud towering above us.
 
Instead, we watch the oncoming frame-bent jeeps as they roaring around the blind corners on bald tires. In Tsarang, the drivers share a rough kindness with us. We play snooker, a game we donâ€™t know. Cory tries and fails to find a tutorial on YouTube. Nursing warm cans of beer, we realize the drivers donâ€™t know how to play either.
 
The evening passes in one long, impossible game of scratches and flubs until the young man running the hall flicks the light switch and kicks us out into the cold, thin air of a star-streaked night.  @vacheronconstantin

Our hearts remain with the thousands of families that have lost loved ones in the 6.4 magnitude earthquake in West Nepal. As winter approaches, tens of thousands remain without adequate shelter or warmth. If youâ€™d like to contribute please visit Blinknow.org - these are friends of ours working tirelessly on the ground, and every contribution matters.

We will resume our Mustang travelogue starting today to celebrate all the beauty, resiliency, and magic of Nepal in the faith that if we all work together, brighter days will come soon. // following words by @jetbutterflies Hoping for mountains, we find fog. Climbing towards Sarangkot, the city disappears behind us. Marigolds line the road that falls away into steeped terraces dotted by clusters of roughhewn homes. An hour in, we find the main highway again, paved and twisted into tight curls across the steep hillsides like a pigâ€™s tail. Toddâ€™s back wheel blows up, death-wobbling him across the narrow road and directly into a stable of split-open motor scooters under a corrugated tin roof held together with wire.

The mechanic opens the rear tire, and leaves the parts strewn across the shoulder of the highway. A metal-handled hammer and broken screwdriver finish the job: a blown bearing. The mechanic isnâ€™t much of a talker. He saddles a scooter and buzzes off to somewhere while the town gathers around us, sharing stories and children and a, most proudly, new iPhone 12 ProMax.  They return with two bearings â€“ â€œJapanâ€ brand. â€œBest qualityâ€, he says.
Four hours of riding to go. @vacheronconstantin @aetherapparel

The thing about earthquakes is that they impact poor and vulnerable communities the most. Those who canâ€™t afford to reinforce their homes, or who donâ€™t have a surplus of resources like family, income, or grain to weather months of rebuilding and trauma.

In light of the recent 6.4 magnitude earthquake that struck Western Nepal last night - just miles from Mustang - and our hope to focus public attention on supporting relief efforts, we will postpone our travelogue until next week.

Currently, there are 150+ known deaths from the quake with many hundreds more injured and tens of thousands left without shelter as winter approaches. Please watch this space for updates on how you can help the families in Jajarkot and Rukum recover and build back better.

With love, 
Cory and Ben

Words by Ben Ayers @jetbutterflies // The highway is a perpetual a fever dream of construction and destruction. Dust, scattered pavement, clawed ridges of clay are punctuated with the idle carcasses of heavy equipment, thin herds of goats, and garish tractors bouncing between knee-deep ruts. When you donâ€™t have any lanes, youâ€™re always splitting lanes.
 
Six days ago, Cory did what any responsible motorcyclist would do: he watched a YouTube video titled â€œHow to Ride a Motorcycle in ONLY 1 HOUR,â€ which, it turns out, was only twenty minutes long. 
 
Cory then traced the backstreets of Santa Monica on a tiny cafÃ© racer for five days before boarding a plane for Kathmandu. Now, eight hours of riding on Nepalâ€™s worst and busiest highway later, the sun collapses across rice paddies heavy with grain. We still have hours to go.
 
In this perpetual present, when youâ€™re gripped, you experience the relativity of time. It slows to a game of seconds until, as if by magic, hours have passed.

Iâ€™ve known Ben Ayers @jetbutterflies for over a decade. Heâ€™s a Kathmandu staple and has called Nepal home for twenty some years. He came for the mountains and stayed for the people, starting and running non-profits for pieces of the community. At his heart, heâ€™s an artist and filmmaker. Heâ€™s also a ferocious writer. Iâ€™ve been to Mustang with him before on assignment for NG. But this trip is just for us. The following posts are his words.
 
Our other companion is Todd Hoffman. He doesnâ€™t use Instagram. Heâ€™s one of those leather-faced legends of the eighties who lived hard and fast enough to know when to leave the racetrack. Even if you hardly know him, you want him on your team. At your back. If he looks familiar, it might be from that one time he took Pepsi to task over a Harrier jump jet.

More views from Vienna, this time from October 2023 on the new Phoenix color film.

The last few years have been (mostly) good for analog photography: the new Leica M6, increased use of ECN-2 film stocks and processing, news of a new line of Pentax film cameras â€”Â while weâ€™re also facing rising film prices and ongoing economic issues elsewhere, Iâ€™ll take positive news when it comes.

When Phoenix was released, there was a certain amount of negativity about who was sent sample rolls as the launch coverage and reviews rolled out. The common complaint was that it was only sent to â€œinfluencersâ€ â€”Â not a term I love, though people with influence have always been a good strategy for getting the word out.

The implication was that if Phoenix had been sent to â€œrealâ€ photographers for testing, the images would have been better, or the reviews wouldnâ€™t have been as favorable, etc. â€” and that the generally-positive public feedback on the new film was only due to said influencers not wanting to get on Harmanâ€™s bad side.

This sort of commentary smells like jealousy, and I get it â€”Â there are a LOT of amazing photographers out there who havenâ€™t been blessed by social mediaâ€™s algorithmic deities, and it can be frustrating to see opportunities being handed to other people when you feel you could do better. However, indignance doesnâ€™t do anyone any favors.

Itâ€™s also easy to be jaded, and say companies like @harmanphoto are making a money-grab by selling a limited edition product â€”Â though Iâ€™d wager most of the folks who made that argument happily took advantage of Black Friday deals.

Harman launched a new, niche product, and you canâ€™t do that without promotion â€”Â if you can get the bulk of your press by sending people free product, more power to you.

So, let people be excited about new film! The world has enough darkness right now â€”Â choose to shine a light where you can.

(Continued in comments)

Heading back to Vienna next week â€” one of my favorite cities â€” to run another mini-workshop and photowalk with my buddy Jahan (@doyoudevelop) and the good folks at @leica_akademie_austria & @leica_camera_austria. Link in my bio + Stories, et al.

This time weâ€™re digging into high-speed B&W film (3200ISO, pushing film, and the like), so I thought Iâ€™d share some images Iâ€™ve been sitting on for a while.

In February 2020, I was in Vienna for a few weeks and brought along a camera Iâ€™d had in my collection for years but never used: a Kodak Retina 1a from 1953.

I slowly captured a single roll of HP5+ while wandering Viennaâ€™s streets, zone focusing at f11â€“16, pushing the roll 1-stop (effectively turning 400ISO film into 800ISO) to keep the shutter speeds higher at those smaller apertures.

Iâ€™ll share some more from this roll in a few days â€” itâ€™ll be nice to revisit Vienna on high-speed B&W film nearly 4 years on ğŸï¸

â€œHi Anna. Our brigade surrenders in captivity today. Me too. I donâ€™t know what will happen next. I love you all.â€
_____________

Waiting for Serhiy

His attempts to escape the Russian siege had failed. He and his fellow Ukrainian Marines were surrounded, dozens of miles from friendly lines. They were nearly out of food and ammunition. Some panicked, others quietly resigned themselves to what would come next.
Then, a few days later, senior sailor Sergey Hrebinyk and his comrades emerged from the sprawling Ilyich Iron and Steel works in the southern Ukrainian city of Mariupol. He quickly messaged his older sister: â€œHi Anna. Our brigade surrenders. In captivity today. I also donâ€™t know what will happen next. I love you.â€
It was April 12, 2022.

Nearly two years later, on the second anniversary of the start of Russiaâ€™s full scale invasion, Serhiy Hrebinyk, 24, remains in captivity as a prisoner of war, held somewhere in Russia. His family sits in purgatory, trapped between that day in April and the present.

The initial panicked flurry of calls to the Red Cross, the Ukrainian military and local officials subsided as official proof of life took months to come. The war dragged on, and now, like thousands of other Ukrainian families with relatives in captivity, the Hrebinyks wait.

â€œLife, of course, has changed. Almost every day is filled with tears,â€ said Svitlana Hrebinyk, Serhiyâ€™s mother.

Words @tmgneff Photos @dguttenfelder Editing @adamjdean for @nytimes in Sumy. Ukraine marking two years of war since the full-scale Russian invasion.

Ukrainian soldiers rested inside a destroyed building on the edge of the newly liberated but desolate village of Blahodatne. It was one of seven villages that Ukraine had retaken during the early days of the counteroffensive against Russia and just one of dozens, or hundreds that would need to be bled over if their strategy could succeed. 

This photograph is part of the @nytimes 2023 The Year In Pictures. Itâ€™s been a year of very dark days and unprecedented danger for fellow journalists in Gaza and Lebanon, Israel, Ukraine...

Emerging from an underground bunker in a tree line, Ukrainian soldiers fired their 50+ year old Soviet-era artillery at Russian frontline infantry near Bakhmut. 

The town cleared another acre of ground and began digging fresh graves to make room for many of the 52 killed in one vicious Russian missile strike on mourners whoâ€™d gathered for a wake in the village of Hroza. 

A steady flow of injured soldiers, cared for by combat medics in this hidden Donetsk region outpost. 

Boots and bloody clothing, cut away from injured Ukrainian soldiers before evacuation from the front, were heaped in the hallway and yard at one combat medic outpost in the Kupiansk direction.

Yuri, a Ukrainian villager from Hroza, wandered in the ruins. His wife Halyna died here the day before.

A self portrait series from just a few weeks ago in Deadvlei, Namibia.  A place Iâ€™ve dreamed of visiting for a decadeâ€¦ and yet being there in person, walking barefoot across the dead marsh under these 600-900 year old skeleton trees, was such a surreal experience unlike what I imagined it would be.  Itâ€™s strange to walk through a place that feels so long dead and forgotten - yet still full of life and wonder.

I originally had an entirely different series of images in my mind for here, involving a couple of different colourful dresses (red and gold) and dance poses mimicking and flowing with these treesâ€¦ but when I arrived here, just as the sun rose and lit up my surroundings and as I walked over the last sand dune to see the dead pan valley floor below, all those earlier visions I had simply vanished. Thankfully, tucked away in the bottom of my backpack under my camera gear and red/gold dresses (anyone else cram dresses and chocolate into their backpack as a general hiking norm?), I had also this white dress as a back-upâ€¦ and I was so glad I brought it, because all I could actually envision in person here was a balance of death and life, light and dark, a dream walking through decay. 

And so thatâ€™s how I spent the next 3 hours - walking and running around barefoot, feeling connection, contrast and awe, and creating this new series as it came to me. ğŸ¤ What a surreal place.

Itâ€™s a time where I somehow feel far less guilty about letting my mind and life slow down, where I can become like the trees and the bears in winter, resting quietly and hibernating from the world in my own little introverted cocoon.  Itâ€™s in the soft, quiet, candle-lit hours that I feel the most rested and at peace, and therefore more renewed and rekindled with creativity and short bursts of adventurous energy during the day - when these short hours of daylight are a gift, appreciated even more in the winter. ğŸ¥°

How often do you stop to measure your successes? I find it is usually easier to remember the difficult times, but in this moment, I would like to honor all that we have accomplished.

In the past 10 years since starting Modern MacramÃ©, I have traveled the world teaching plant and wall-hanging workshops. I always dreamed of traveling for work, and I was lucky to be welcomed to teach in Mexico City, Barcelona, Copenhagen, Kyoto, Berlin, London, Amsterdam, and many more places. I visited our rope supplier in Turkey. 

In 2018 wrote a book about macramÃ© that finally paid out the advance this week! Woot! (a new book idea is brewing!)
 

I toured the USA in a mini van with my friend Caitlin teaching over 50 workshops from coast to coast over 3 months to celebrate that book.

I worked with amazing women in the studio and across the world, my teammates and my students who taught me so much about how to lead, how to be kind, how to ask for what you need, and how to be human. I am still learning. You know who you are.

We as a company sold over $3 million worth of rope, classes, and other craft supplies.
 
Our work helped launch the careers of small craft business owners around the globe. - continued in slides and comments

AMG GT Black Series â€The Endgameâ€œ.

Back in the days, the most powerful AMG V8 series engine of all time, the most expressive design, the most elaborate aerodynamics, the most intelligent material mix, the most distinctive driving dynamics: For the new Mercedes-AMG GT Black Series (combined fuel consumption 12.8 l/100 km, combined CO2 emissions 292 g/km)[1], the Affalterbach designers have pulled out all the stops when it comes to the art of vehicle design.

The super sports car perfectly embodies the brandâ€™s rich tradition in motorsport, as well its many years of expertise in developing complete vehicles which impress in every respect. The result is an output of 537 kW (730 hp) from a V8 engine with a â€šflatâ€˜ crankshaft, combined with active aerodynamics and a design which stems directly from the current AMG GT3 racing car.

Different designs of V8 engines.

The design of a V8 engine gives designers plenty of room to play with in one key element: the crank arrangement on the crankshaft.
The result is the most powerful V8 series engine from Mercedes-AMG.

The GT Black Series engine may be based on the AMG 4.0-litre V8 biturbo engine with dry sump lubrication, but it has been given the new internal code M178 LS2 due to the numerous modifications. It achieves 730hp at 6700-6900 rpm and delivers a maximum torque of 800Nm at 2000-6000 rpm. New camshafts and exhaust manifolds are adapted to the new firing order and further improve the gas cycle.

Both twin scroll exhaust turbochargers are mounted in anti-friction bearings, as in the top-of-the-range four-door AMG GT CoupeÌ, which optimises their throttle response even further. However, in the Black Series, the turbochargers have been given a larger compressor wheel, meaning that both can deliver a total of 1100 kg air per hour.

This week the USDA announced that there are fewer farms in the U.S. than at any time since 1850, and 40% of them are owned by people over age 65.  In most industrialized countries, farmers are less than 2% of the population and shrinking.  Here, Doug Hellinger is driving a weed sprayer past the homestead that his grandmother established near Shelby, Montana, shortly after 1909, when the Homestead Act gave 320 acres for free if you farmed the land for five years.  At that time, there were 72 families per 36 sq miles, and today, just 8 people remain, including Doug.

Always good to have friends in high places.  I had the easy job on this helicopter shoot for @nytmag a few years ago, with @jimmychin hanging over the rail while photographing a maintenance worker climbing up the antenna of One World Trade. Jimmy and his amazing wife @chaivasarhelyi have gone on to scale the heights of Hollywood, but when I ran into Jimmy last week he sheepishly declared â€œIâ€™m still just a dirtbag climber.â€ Arenâ€™t we all?

Looking for covers for my next book today, and I came across this forgotten image from the soybean harvest in Brazil two years ago.  Soybean production in Brazil is almost ten times what it was in 1985, and those numbers continue to rise to meet Chinaâ€™s growing demand for pig food. Much of that new production is from land that was once forest.

Volcanic crater of Wau al Namus (hole of mosquitos) in Arabic. 
This massive volcano can easily be seen in satellite views of Southern Libya, as a large black smear in the wind-scoured sands of the Sahara.  The inner crater is bordered by a chain of small salt lakes which are sumps for underground springs). Outside the rim are small black dunes of windblown volcanic ejecta.  It was difficult getting there with my motorized paraglider during the time of Gadaffi, but would be even more complicated today. Carpe diem!
So nice to see my photo above the fold on front page of todayâ€™s @NYTimes!  To see more and read the story on-line, go to link in bio.

Herding over 600 sheep down from the remote high pasture of the Aletsch Glacier Valley in Switzerland.  So happy to see this story about the effects of climate change in the Alps in todayâ€™s @nytimes

Herding 145,000 sheep and goats onto a livestock carrier in the port of Berbera, Somaliland last July for shipment to Mecca in Saudi Arabia, where 2.6 million animals were ritually sacrificed on the third day of the Hajj pilgrimage.  According to todayâ€™s @NYTimes, Somaliland has just granted military use of this sleepy deepwater port to landlocked Ethiopia, allowing access to the busy shipping lanes of the Red Sea and Gulf of Aden.  No monetary terms were disclosed, but the deal makes Ethiopia the first nation to recognize the sovereignty of Somaliland, a self-declared democratic republic in one of the worldâ€™s poorest regions.  Last year, live animal exports were 85% of Somalilandâ€™s export earnings and 30% of its GDP, but that may be about to change.

Snowmobile with sled passing under the Atyrau Bridge on the frozen Yesil River, Astana, Kazakhstan.  The bridge was designed by young local architects who were inspired by the shape of the endemic Caspian Sturgeon.

Every time I go to #Finland I come back a little more playful and a little more curious in the best possible way. Itâ€™s actually really hard to put this magic into words but itâ€™s a really special place.

Last year I travelled to #OulankaNationalPark to experience the trip curated by @exodustravels that combined the best of winter activities with a real tangible purpose. Whilst exploring we were sampling the rivers for eDNA, which is a relatively new technology to monitor and record local biodiversity.

For me, having had the privilege of travelling the world, the purpose of this trip really sets it a cut above a regular holiday.

You can read more about this particular trip by following the link on my stories, or just search Finnish Wilderness Week or Citizen Science on Exodus.co.uk #CitizenScience #ExodusTravels #AdventureTravel

Flew to the land down under few days ago and I finally got to see Canberra. I must say this beautiful city is more quiet and laidback as compared to the vibrant and busy Sydney.

With many things in mind, visiting the National Gallery of Australia is on the top our list. Inside it we saw a lot of amazing masterpieces, but what struck me the most is James Turrell's 'Within without' Skyspace, a viewing chamber (or a "stupa") highlighted by turquoise water that surrounds it. This work shows the way we percieve the sky depending on the time of the day. They say it is at its most dramatic and complex form during dawn and dusk, marking the transition between day and night. Truly a remarkable work of art where nature, art, and architecture meet!

Excited to share more snaps and stories from the many things we saw and learned about this city. Big thanks to my travel partner @bigskynationph for keeping us connected everywhere we go with their travel wi-fi!

The beetle of rebirth ğŸª²ğŸŒ
At the end of November 2021 we were at a friends house about to leave when a golden beetle posed on my hand. It had been a long time since I saw one or at least payed close attention to it. I feel that many times we experience things often but donâ€™t really give importance to them until we feel it is needed, then it becomes something meaningful. I started drawing the beetle on my notebook, carefully placed the insect on my finger it was holding my index with his tiny legs and thought about a ring! 
It gave me nostalgia of when the world was different and when we could travel, reminded me of our time in Egypt and in some way gave me hope, Cairo 2019 was also where I first saw a beetle ring from Tutankamon in the museum. I was amazed by Egyptian culture, art and mostly jewelry I thought it was cool but I never really questioned the symbolism of the elements and characters they used back then and why, but that day the golden beetle that posed on my hand made me curious and I started reaserching what it means, the meaning varies depending the culture but what I took from the Egyptians is that: the beetle symbolized the sun, a new day, a new opportunity, a cicle, knowing that the sun rises every day no matter what, rebirth! I thought the meaning was beautiful and felt like the right timing for me to start a process of â€œrebirthâ€ this was right before 2021 ended, 

which had been a though year, I was not feeling too motivated, my grandma had just passed away a couple months before, and some little struggles that made me feel a bit stuck and not at my best. I didnâ€™t know it at the time but from that day it was going to take 5 months to have the finished ring in my hands. Not because the actual process takes that long but in a way I wanted to have it ready whenever I felt better with myself, finishing this ring will mean to have a rebirth in a way, learnt the lessons, feel more motivated and in a better mental space.

I saw @karlieplace post a bit of this editing style on a reel yesterday and I just thought it was amazing. Shout out to hers, you should definitely go check it out. 

When I see the dodge/burn notes on old film prints itâ€™s a reminder that the art and intention of the shot doesnâ€™t end until itâ€™s delivered. I imagine some people would rather enjoy the magic without seeing how the sausage is made but I LOVE editing and always have.

I came up in this industry at a time where there was this odd mystique and elitism that I thankfully avoided, but I saw it discourage SO many people. And there was a tension because my income was also tied to education regarding editing and presets, and carving out a brand that was uniquely my voice. Iâ€™d much rather contribute to the shared pool of liberating knowledge so that the beautiful thing you were meant to do is not trapped behind something as dull as tone curves and split toning. 

The anchors of journalistic integrity are different than those for eliciting emotion. But you are also free to, and encouraged to, be unashamed about what does and doesnâ€™t land with your creative preference. Just donâ€™t make that the primary thing about your engagements with people on the internet. 

As always if you have questions about my process, whether it be gear, software, how I think about what I do, or anything else Iâ€™d so much rather communicate than get a â€˜likeâ€™.

The truth about ALMOND CROISSANTSğŸ¥

Croissants go stale so quickly!! So hereâ€™s what you can do when you have a few extra ones laying around :) Or if you donâ€™t want to pay the almond croissant premium LOL.

âœ¨Ingredients:
â€¢1 cup water
â€¢1/3 cup sugar

â€¢4 croissants
â€¢25 gr unsalted butter
â€¢60 gr cane sugar
â€¢60 gr almond flour
â€¢1 medium egg
â€¢1 tsp vanilla extract
â€¢sliced almonds
â€¢powder sugar for dusting

In a small saucepan, bring water and 1/3 cup of sugar to a boil to make a syrup. Cool down. Preheat oven 350Â°F and cut croissants in half. In a bowl, combine softened unsalted butter with sugar. Then add almond flour, combine, and lastly add egg and vanilla to form an almost paste. Brush sugar syrup on the inside and outside of the croissant and then spread the almond paste inside. Close the croissant and spread more paste on top and top off with sliced almonds. Bake for 15-18 mins, cool down, and dust with powdered sugar. Enjoy!

EASY SPICY TUNA POKE BOWLSğŸŸğŸ¥£ğŸŒ¶ï¸ (full recipe below)

I think spicy tuna bowls are the new hot girl meal. I know raw fish can be a little intimidating, so make sure you buy previously flash-frozen fish from a grocer that you trust! I buy my ahi tuna filets from @Sprouts and eat them the day of.

âœ¨Ingredients (4 servings) // about 60gr protein per portion 

-1 1/2 lbs raw ahi tuna (2 steaks)
-1 1/2 tbsp sriracha
-2-3 tbsp aminos or soy sauce
-3 tbsp Kewpie mayonnaise
-1 cup edamame
-1 hass avocado
-1 cup uncooked sushi rice
-1 tbsp mirin
-1 tbsp rice vinegar
-1/2 tbsp sesame oil
-1 tsp salt
-1 tsp sesame seeds

Pat dry ahi tuna and cut it into 1-inch cubes. Place inside a bowl and add sriracha, aminos, and mayo. Stir until combined, cover, and rest refrigerated for at least 15 minutes. Cook sushi rice according to the instructions on the package. Warm up frozen edamame by pouring boiling water on top and letting it sit for 5 minutes. Slice avocado or mash it; feel free to season it however you like. Add mirin, rice vinegar, sesame oil, and salt to cooked rice. Stir and use it as a base for your bowl. Continue plating by adding about 4 ounces of tuna, 1/4 cup of edamame, and 1/4-1/2 an avocado. Portions are up to you! Top with sesame seeds, and feel free to add any extra sauce and seasonings like furikake. Enjoy immediately and save any leftovers in a tight-lid container in the fridge. Eat the same day.

SAVE this for a quick Egg Free Breakfast option!

RECIPE

-1-2 cups finely chopped broccoli florets (optional, but a great way to add greens into breakfast!)
-1 cup your choice of gluten free flour (I used Bobâ€™s Red Mill Paleo All Purpose mix)
-1 tsp baking powder

-3/4 cup Almond Milk (or your choice of milk)
â€”
â€¢SautÃ© 1 lb breakfast sausage & finely chopped broccoli florets in avocado oil until sausage is fully cooked 
â€¢In a mixing bowl, add 1 cup gluten free flour, 
1 tsp baking powder, & mix together. 
â€¢Then add 1 cup shredded cheese. Mix all together.
â€¢Add and mix in cooked sausage & broccoli to the dry mix.

â€¢Scoop mixture into pre-greased cupcake pan- I use avocado oil spray.

â€œFurnitureâ€¦ lots of furniture!â€ @klekktic 

The Matrix is one of my all time favourite movies. It came out 25 years ago, inspiring a whole generation of filmmakers, visual effects artists and stunt coordinators. 

This is my take on the iconic â€œguns, lots of gunsâ€ scene where Neo & Trinity enter The Matrix to prepare for battle. I thought this would be a fun and innovative way of showcasing a furniture brand. Having different products from the @klekktic collection flying into the Matrix. 

To execute this @shravanraoo & I shot for a full 12 hours in a studio in Dubai. Heba, the founder of Klekktic, who plays Trinity in this video, helped coordinate all of the Klekktic pieces to be shipped to the studio. We then placed each item one by one filming the product and then removing it. This allowed us to create the effect of different pieces flying into place.

@Klekktic is a beautiful UAE based brand. They have a minimal design aesthetic that is clean and elegant. The best part about their products is they are customizable. For example, the desk at the start of the video I fully customized from a dining room table into an office desk with draws and storage. Bed sizes, table lengths, mirror finishings etc can all be customized to fit your space size and preference. 

My home project is really starting to take shape. Itâ€™s been a long time coming but itâ€™s been worth the wait. More coming on that soonâ€¦

Special shout out to @shravanraoo who helped me film this and then worked on the kick ass visual effects.

Back in July I had the opportunity to spend a few weeks in Venezuela creating something special for @beautifuldestinations. 

As 2023 has been the year of AI, Iâ€™ve been wanting to innovate and figure out a way to combine new immersive AI visuals with travel content. My thinking was that weâ€™d be going to a place that not many people have seen before, Angel Falls in Canaima National Park, and if we could combine never before seen AI content with a truly out of this world destination then weâ€™d have all the ingredients for something special.

The idea developed into a FPV Drone only concept where weâ€™d play with generative AI to add little details into the video. @reme_martyr then joined the team to execute the aerials, he killed it! As the concept got bigger so did the team with @alexislefrene , @shravanraoo , @andres.visual and @bahaamalaeb joining the squad. 

What started as a fun idea turned into a full blown innovation project, looking to create the worldâ€™s first AI supported Tourism Campaign. By tapping into unique visual styles the hope was to create something that would make some noise and spark a conversation about the destination.

This was 'Blood Swept Lands and Seas of Red', an art installation at the Tower of London consisting of 888,246 ceramic poppies - one for each British and Colonial soldier who died during the war. It commemorated the 100th year since Britain's first day in the First World War. The first poppy was planted on the 5th August, with the 888,246th poppy being planted on 11th November 2014. Each of the poppies was sold to charity raising millions for six associated charities. It is now 105 years since the armistice was signed between the Allies and Germany, ceasing a war in which an estimated 37,000,000 people died. #remembranceday #toweroflondon

news flash: last week, just north of cabo near our hotel in baja, a mama sea turtle came ashore to lay a clutch of eggs. she made three nests, spending ~20 minutes in each (the first and last nest are visible in the second video) and used her fins to push sand and bury herself deeper into the sand before laying the eggs, before making her way back to the ocean and vanishing into a wave. according to the man in this video, the eggs should hatch in 1-2 months and the turtles (loggerheads) lay several nests in order to maximize reproductive output + help protect the eggs from predators ğŸ¢

â€œconflict in congo is like a babushka (matryoshka) doll....you have conflicts sitting inside conflicts....itâ€™s about local issues, who controls land, which chief is in power....often linked to ethnicity, because at local level ethnicity is the principle organizer of politics....at the next level, it is national power, partially due to collapse of mobutu and effects of belgian colonialism....but there it is more about using ethnicity to leverage a better position in parliament or a piece of a smuggling racket in gold....then you have the regional power politics, which mainly involves rwanda and that role really began in 1994 with the rwandan genocide....the conflict initially was not about minerals, though they became important over time to fund war efforts, esp for a country like rwanda that is small and poor....but when tantalum shot through the roof, which happened to be at a time of extreme violence, it began to shift incentives of those involved in the conflict and it was no longer about national security....around 2000 the various actors became more invested in minerals....but the war here is really about power and access to power, and that passes through local politicians. so you need to understand the politicsâ€ - jason stearns

*note: the above may serve to help understand the â€œconflict in congo,â€ the atmosphere inside the country, and is not meant to address the past/current influence of foreign powers â€œoutsideâ€

I was one of nine creators, who embarked on a bus trip from Malaga to Valencia in search of the perfect shot the new Z 8 mirrorless camera.
Packing a host of Z 9 features into a lightweight body, the all-new Z 8 gives image-makers an astounding flexibility to bring our vision to life! 
With its impressive blend of class-leading performance and compact build, this camera is an exciting follow up to the Z 9 and the creative successor to the D850. The Z 8 is a video and stills powerhouse, with key new features such as an in-camera 12-bit RAW for video up to 8.3K/60p or 4.1K/120p, and an array of file sizes and burst speeds for still shooters. 
This is the perfect hybrid camera for creators who want a lighter body for shooting handheld or a full-frame camera that will balance perfectly on any rig, including most gimbals. 
I can't wait for you all to be able to experience this camera and its impressive new features for yourselves!

This is going to be a lot of work and a big part of my life this year. Now that the weather is warming up hopefully I'll be able to start dedicating time to making this dream happen. Who is interested in seeing me build this out?

With my daughter enrolled in public school this year, this is the first year in 6 years that we aren't in Baja during February. I miss the warm weather and being outside every day in the sun but we've still been getting out here in Utah to re-engage with winter and give it another chance. We've been sledding, winter hiking, going to the climbing gym, and teaching my daughter to ski on the weekends. It has been fun but I still prefer the Baja winter life. We decide to enroll Zoey in one more year it public school. She has good teachers and friends which has been great for her but after that are thinking of resuming home schooling and once again returning to Baja for the winter. 
Do you or have you ever traveled to warm places during the winter? Do you love winter or prefer warmer weather? Why?

Big announcement! This is the beginning of a new project that will kick start a new chapter in our livesâ€¦. If I survive how difficult this project will be. For the past 6 years, Iâ€™ve mostly been spending my winters in Baja. In some ways fallen out of love with the long cold days of winter but with my daughter in school and will be for at least one more year, it is time for me to give winter a second chance. This hike up Angels Landing in Zion was a good reminder of how great winter hiking is. This hike is normally so crowded, but during the early morning hours in winter on a snowy day? Hardly anyone and the views are stunning with the yellow, red and orange cliffs covered in winter fluffy snow. I donâ€™t know if Iâ€™ll ever hike it again in the summer but during the winter? Absolutely.

Chasing dreams beneath the waves: after countless hours, I finally speared a Yellowtail and it was a beauty. 30lbs and 51â€ inches which is longer than my 6 year old daughter is tall. From sashimi on the beach to a New Yearâ€™s Prosecco and Panettone trade to a freeze full of fish to enjoy for months, this catch is more than just a trophyâ€”itâ€™s a memory that still has me riding high.

I'm a Utah boy who grew up far from the ocean. I never really had a relationship with it and never really felt comfortable in it but over the past 5 years of coming to Baja where I taught myself to Freedive and spearfish that relationship has grown and given me a much deeper appreciation for what's under the water that covers 71% of our planet. Spearfishing has been my reason to spend a few hours every day in the water, mostly watching and observing the behavior of the sea life and in the right place when something special unexpectedly swims by. A few days ago I shot my biggest fish to date, shown here, which is a 28lbs Leopard Grouper. This fish is delicious, which was processed and put in the freezer so it can feed us for a number of days once we get back to Utah: ğŸ‘Œ

Merry Christmas everyone. We took off for Zoeyâ€™s school break and came down to Baja for the holidays. So much to be grateful for here but I think our favorite aspect of being in Baja, especially this trip without the van, is just being outside all day, every day, from sunrise to after sunset. Feel good to be alive and sharing this life with my favorite humans.

It's the slow life for me now.

Just a few years ago, I traveled from country to country, experiencing something new every week, every day, every minute. I was filled with impressions and experiences, which I cherish deeply and will keep remembering them forever. But I came to realize that the true essence of travel isn't just about the landscapes or the sights.

It's about connections. The kind that grows stronger the longer you stay, becoming a part of communities. Of families.

Mongolia taught me this valuable lesson, and there's no looking back.

Rinpung Monastery, Paro, Bhutan. A â€œdzongâ€ is the word they use  in Bhutan for a fortress/monastery. These beautiful structures with giant walls reveal a lot about Bhutanâ€™s unique culture. But what are they defending? I am just learning, but thereâ€™s a unique confluence of activity inside each Dzong: besides a military fortress, today, Dzongâ€™s are homes for monks, and a spiritual center, but they also house all kinds of officesâ€”think of it like the combination church, DMV, a civil court, an architecture planning office, and anything else related to the cityâ€™s administration. It shows how there is a lack of separation between â€œchurch and stateâ€â€¦ In Bhutan, their philosophical and â€œreligiousâ€ beliefs (some say Buddhism is not a religion, but a philosophical perspective), are integrated with the government, not separated. ğŸŠMore Bhutanese are beginning to dress like Westerners, but when you visit the Dzong, you are required to where the traditional dress of the Bhutanese people. Ah yes, and the chilisâ€¦ I had to include the chilis drying in the sun. Bhutanese add chilis to almost every dish (even in their rice); certainly there will be chilis in every meal! Part of my upcoming story on Zoroastrianism, the oldest monotheistic religion in the world, for @natgeo. Mehernosh, a pallbearer - the person in charge of carrying the dead body at a funeral - walks away from one of the two functioning towers of silence in Karachi.
A tower of silence, known as dakhma, is a circular structure built by Zoroastrians for excarnation - that means the exposure of human corpses to the elements for decomposition - in order to avoid contamination of the soil and other natural elements by the decomposing dead bodies. Carrion birds, usually vultures (though no longer in Karachiâ€¦) and other scavengers, consume the flesh. Skeletal remains are gathered into a central pit where further weathering and continued breakdown occurs. In this dakhma, reflective mirrors have been fitted inside the tower of silence to increase the heat and help the body decomposing faster.
Karachi, a city of 20 millions, has 800 Zoroastrians known as Parsees, 70% of them are above the age of 70 years old. #zoroastrianism #zoroastrian #towerofsilence #towersofsilence #parsi #parsee

I was in the dust with the wrestlers and I looked up and realised that a crowd had formed, a sea of shalwar kamiz. All these men (and 1 woman!! Can you spot her??) had gathered on the edge of a pilgrimage site to watch a spontaneous wrestling match - called Koshti or Malakhro in Baloch. With laughter and agitation, some theatre, itâ€™s the ancestral raw version of the WWF stuff you might have unfortunately seen on TV. Pakistan, Baluchistan province.

I was in Karachi last March, city of 20 million, I love it there. On my pilgrimage in Baluchistan, I met a man who called himself Samundar Baba (Ocean Baba) - he owned boats. Unusual character, long beard and serious looking type, a big hashish smoker. He lived in Lyari, considered a dodgy area although I didnâ€™t think so. I reached out and we met in his house. I was interested in this world of men you can find on fishing boats. So I asked him to bring me. This is the Korangi fishing harbor, one of the largest one in south asia. It can be complicated to photograph there because of authorisation and army nearby. Samundar kindly got me in and I spent a few hours jumping boats as the sun got low.

The original ravers were just getting started. Fun and mad times with the passionate Ishk Ali and his buddies, like Daula Sain. It was day 2 of our 12 days pilgrimage journey, walking together across Sindh and Baluchistan. That is a double cigarette and a sacrificial goat. Pakistan.

2023 is gone, just a number! Itâ€™s been a year filled with travels in Pakistan, Uzbekistan, Spain, Azerbaijan, Canada, Tajikistan, India etcâ€¦
It was interesting to meander through life between being a photographer, a farmer and be present for the family.
I thought of god a bit, all triggered by a story on Zoroastrianism for National Geographic magazine (coming up). How and why do we often inherit the feeling of being watched by God, god like a massive cctv systemâ€¦ religion the opium of the people?
Probably god is busy with a lot more than watching youâ€¦ Is your god a vengeful one or a god that you will live with and whose law you must respect, like gravity? Lots of fun questions with no real need for answers..

Here is a serene scene, mixing all religious influences (at least to my eye!), in a place that has seen Animism, Buddhism, Zoroastrianism and more recently Islam (ismaili faith). Itâ€™s in an â€œostoneâ€, a shrine in Tajikistanâ€™s Wakhan corridor, adorned with ibex and Marco Polo horns - and a triangle of stones for the â€œshiroghâ€ (the candle of cotton dipped in oil), lit for special occasion (for Jumarat, Eid or for Didor, the birthday of the Aga Khan etc). Azom Khon, the caretaker, is praying for me before I leave. It was beautiful so I pulled back and took a picture.

I will be sharing pictures here from my recent travels until I leave for SE Asia on February 20th.
Love and light for 2024.

I saw him and jumped out of the Uaz and took his hand. We walked to his sheep, we had never met but he got the drift, hand in hand. The playful dog is called Kanash, and he is the great shepherd Mamedo Mamed, I took a note of it. Here after a rough train ride we ended up in Jaqorgon, Uzbekistan, near the Afghan border. It was last July, crazy hot but the plov was delicious (rice, mutton, carrots, raisins, spicesâ€¦ the whole works!). 
After much research (it took weeks, thanks @just.laowai ) we found this family that welcomed us. Here, an all-woman ceremony beneath a hand-embroidered suzani marks a sonâ€™s departure to study in the capital, Tashkent. While the woman (partly hidden behind the veil, wearing green) leads the prayer, reciting Quranic verses, others remove a covering to bless the flatbread called nan. This ritual was influenced by Zoroastrianism, the worldâ€™s oldest monotheist religion. I added some images if you slide right, these were all shot that afternoon. Thanks to @jamesbwellford for sticking with it, @sadiequarrier wonder woman, @kristinromey @rabbitearz93 and many more at the Nat Geo office. One of the symbol on the suzani was borrowed from Zoroastrianism and symbolizes the 4 holy elements, fire, water, earth and air. @dimas.sarmangan

Thanks to @nasa astronaut @loralohara who I met today in space (via zoom), I got to look down at our amazing blue planet from the international space station, cruising amidst the cosmic ocean above us. 

Astronaut Oâ€™Hara, five months into a six month mission,  shared many insights about the fragility of our world, how borders vanish and natural systems connect, what life in zero gravity is like, the properties of water (droplets float), how planetary politics stay behind and much, much more. 
It blew my mind. 

The second image by @loralohara shows the entire Grand Canyon in all its eroded wonders in one single frame. It amazes me to think that it took me 71 days on foot to walk the length of that natural wonder, but the space station crosses it in seconds. 

Thanks again Oâ€™Hara and NASA for reminding us all the wonders we have not just in space, but right on our one shared home.

I finished my 4 day trip to Austria and it's surely been nothing less than surreal. Being at the places which I just saw in mobile wallpapers, even when I was staring at the structures, I wasn't able to believe if this was actually happening. As I walked through, I tried to absorb every sight, every curve on the building, every turn of the road, every small piece of it made me realize why I love to travel. Entering random streets, talking to locals, navigating through public transport, shopping through local groceries, trying to live the culture that has been passed on over the years to form the country what it is today. It's much more than just fancy pictures, these reels or my lame stories I've been spamming with, it's breathing this air and being here. I'd be travelling to four more places on this trip and I don't know which one I would find the best, but this surely made a place in my heart.
.
.
.
.

Located 14 stories high - 200 feet above ground, lies an outdoor urban oasis, where @fairmontroyalyork garden grows. On any summer's day, @chef_jwfoster and the Planet 21 Team can be seen nurturing and tending to the vast variety of organic produce and herbs that are cared for without the use of herbicides and pesticides.

Fairmont also houses six beehives. It is the first of the Fairmont hives and is often noted as being the first rooftop apiary found at any hotel in the world. It was also the first to install a pollinator bee hotel in 2014, paving the way for more to follow in the following years. 

At its summer peak 350,000 honeybees reside in six beehives to produce an average of 450 pounds of honey per year. 

For almost 30 years, Fairmont Hotels has been committed to proactively protecting its local environments. 

A commitment to minimizing its impact on the planet.

MOBILITY FOR TIGHT HIPS ğŸ’« These are some of my favourite hip releases ğŸ‘ŒğŸ¼ Perfect to do as part of your warm up, before a run, on a recovery day or when you are feeling a bit sore/tired from trainingâ€¦ I sometimes get lower back tightness and these also help release tension & pain! â˜ºï¸

â–ªï¸1. LOW SQUAT
- lower your hips to any position that is manageable and where you can keep your heels on the ground & elbows inside the knees (Level 1,2 & 3 shown in order in the video â˜ºï¸)
- if you can reach level 3, aim to pull your belly & chest forward at the bottom, spreading the knees wide.
AREAS RELEASED - Groin, hamstrings, low back

â–ªï¸2. LOW LUNGE RAINBOW DIVE
- as you reach back open your chest as much as possible & sink the hips.
- guide the elbow toward the ground reaching as low as you can.
AREAS RELEASED - Groin, hip flexor, glute, hamstring, low back

â–ªï¸3. GLUTE SLIDE
- foot rests close to the opposite hand as knee slides through the arms as far as you can.
- for a deeper release, slide the back knee further back into a longer lunge.
AREAS RELEASED - Glutes, hip flexor, hamstrings, low back

Kenya is reclaiming its role as a haven for eastern black rhinos, establishing a vital breeding population of 21 rhinos at @Loisaba_Conservancy in Laikipia, Kenya, where they have been absent for the past half-century. But moving a black rhino, an animal weighing over a ton, is a Herculean challenge fraught with danger at every turn. It begins with the risky task of sedating the massive creature, a procedure that requires precision and caution to ensure both the rhinoâ€™s safety and that of the vets and handlers. Once subdued, the real test begins as the sedated rhino must be carefully revived and maneuvered into a sturdy crate, a task made all the more daunting by the animalâ€™s immense size and strength. Every step of this delicate operation underscores the inherent risks involved. Watch the sheer force this rhino unleashes as he awakens and imagine doing this 20 more times over the course of 2 weeks. The teams from @kenyawildlifeservice executed the operation with unparalleled expertise and dedication.  In an ideal world, we wouldnâ€™t have to go through these extreme measures but with approximately 80% of the worldâ€™s remaining eastern black rhinos under its protection, Kenyaâ€™s efforts offer a glimmer of hope for the future of these magnificent creatures.

I am humbled to share another remarkable conservation story from Kenya: the resurgence of eastern black rhinos from the brink of extinction. In a pivotal moment, Kenya is reclaiming its role as a haven for these creatures, establishing a vital breeding population at @Loisaba_Conservancy in Laikipia, Kenya, where they have been absent for the past half-century mainly due to poaching and long ago,  trophy hunting. This first image shows the moment a rhino was resuscitated after it stopped breathing and quickly released. The arduous tasks of tracking, darting, and relocating 21 of these critically endangered giants, each weighing over a ton, posed formidable challenges, yet the teams from @kenyawildlifeservice executed the operation with unparalleled expertise and dedication. Their efforts offer a glimmer of hope for the future of these magnificent creatures. The final image shows the skull of the last rhino poached in the 1970s resting beneath a celestial canopy, symbolizing this hopeful shift as Kenya now stands  as a nation that is expanding habitat and bolstering rhino populations. With approximately 80% of the world's remaining eastern black rhinos under its protection, Kenya is safeguarding endangered populations for future generations.

The way I see it, â€œMobilityâ€ Is kind of like a collaboration effort between our muscles and joints.
 
When our joint mobility is limited, we might be missing out on opportunities to be stronger, more athletic, and more efficient.
 
The ability to move our joints through their full range helps our muscles work more optimally, and when our muscles can do their work, they can also get stronger and help keep our joints healthy in return.
 
ğŸ’ªğŸ¼Having a good balance between strength and joint mobility helps distribute the stress more evenly through the body instead of overstressing our joints (back, hips, knees, ankles, etc.).
 
ğŸšªOur joints are kind of like the hinges to a door; if that door remains unopened for long periods in addition to environmental decay, the hinges in that door will start creaking and get rusty overtime. In our case, it will be arthritis, bursitis, inflammation, and things like that.
 
So you see, just as with the door example, maintenance and movement were keys to extending the life and function of it, in our case, MAINTENANCE and MOVEMENT are also keys to a BETTER QUALITY OF LIFE.ğŸ™ŒğŸ¼

Angkor Wat and park in Siem Reap, Cambodia. This is my second time here and it still feels as mystical as the first time. At the beginning of our tour, our guide overwhelmed us with all the mathematical calculations and engineering ingenuity that went into building Angkor Wat. Certain points of the structure lined up perfectly with the Draco Constellation and the sun positioning at sunset. Although there are educated speculation from experts archeologists saying this dates back about 900 years ago, Itâ€™s all a mystery.

On the other hand, Spiritual channelers have mentioned this to be older than 5000 BC. Itâ€™s a place to activate the pineal gland (third eye) through frequencies, itâ€™s also an informational point for earth to funnel data to and from other planets/galaxies. Itâ€™s like another access point of information like the great pyramids. The art carvings hold a lot of relations to Hinduism on many of the Angkor Park structures. But personally, I see a lot of psychedelic reflections on some of the temples. They almost look like what I see as the crossover realm between the mind and other outer dimensions. Itâ€™s like the level where you have to overcome the ego before connecting with your higher self. Very interesting place to walk around and wander off into.

This town is 2 hrs south of Saigon - which around $40 Grab ride.  The town itself is pretty developed as in roads and sidewalks, but this is where you can relax from the crazy traffic and roads of Saigon. I think Ben Tre fits the criteria of what many people think of Saigon. Itâ€™s a growing city, with no crazy developments, or high rise.  Many restaurants or stores here cater to the locals, so you will get more of an authentic experience. The locals are pretty friendly as long as you are respectful. The kids like to say â€œhelloâ€ to my bf because they want to use their English. They get a good chuckle when he says â€œhiâ€ in Vietnamese. We usually greet and thanks in the language of the country weâ€™re in, many folks seem to appreciate it.  The young locals speak English well, older people usually donâ€™t. 

We did 3 tours here with @mrbikerbentreboattour , Troy found him on TripAdvisor. We highly recommend his tours. After doing our first private boat tour, we came back for another tour of the town, and then rented bikes from one of the eco lodges/homestays. @mrbikerbentreboattour has been extremely punctual and helpful with us. His tours gives you a sample of the local lifestyle and Vietnamese tradition. Weâ€™ve got to visit the small canals off the Mekong river, and private roads of the locals. We did not experienced any upsell, pressure to buy, or nonsense stops on the tours. Great place for coffee and plant enthusiasts ğŸª´ There were little tables and seats hidden around an array of hanging plants. Later I found out it was a plant shop too! This was a nice little break stop for another refresher. Troy got his iced coffee and so we got to sit amongst all these pretty greenery. Everything is such a contrast in Saigon. You see old vs new everywhere, the crazy busy hustle of traffic, and Vietnamese taking their naps in the mist of all the chaos in the streets. I really enjoy observing ğŸ‘€ and wondering how people adapt to the places they live in. 
.

There are so many fun cafes here! My favorite part of the day is going out in the morning to try a new coffee or tea at a new cafeğŸ§¡ğŸ˜‹ The iced lattes are only around $1 vs $7 in the states ğŸ˜£ There are like tones of cafes side by side on every block and I am in love with that! â˜•ï¸ You also donâ€™t have to worry about people taking up space with their laptops on the tables. At night, the cafes are more bustling with people mingling and sipping on iced tea. If I have more time here, I would probably visit a new coffee shop everyday ğŸ§¡

My Barbie moment at a super pink church in Saigon! Itâ€™s incredibly hot here but I heard itâ€™s -25 back home, so weâ€™re not complaining! Iâ€™ll take this heat and over stimulated city for the time being ğŸ§¡ 

I thought that crowded places gives me anxiety but what I learned is that the environment and people affect me. Crowded places donâ€™t give me anxiety, the collective energy of the same things do. Sometimes my environment can feel like a drag. People talking about the same things, focused on career, status, gossip, politics, limited beliefs, problems after problems. And when Iâ€™m around it too much, it sucks the life force out of me, so I retract. Exploring helps me break free from that. Any sort of traveling, mini trips, or taking off on a plane helps me break free from monotony and repetition. Walking in places is also very grounding for me. Iâ€™ve noticed that I need a balance of both worlds, the chaotic city and being in nature. When I become extreme in one, I definitely can feel the lack of balance in my overall energy. We are all different and Iâ€™m learning more on how to listen to my personal inner guide. #saigon #vietnam

Anthony Bourdain made a lot of videos  in Vietnam. He definitely created a pathway for international foodies to embrace itâ€™s unique culture. A lot has changed here in development but some of his recommended stops are still around. This place specializes on one of my favorite dishes, Banh Xeo! Banh Xeo looks like an omelette; but itâ€™s not, itâ€™s rice flour, turmeric gives it the yellow color, some people add coconut milk, and beer to the batter making the outer crepe shell crispy.  Itâ€™s a nicely light dish and can make a great appetizer. Itâ€™s often served with a heaping plate of fresh lettuce and herbs. You roll everything up in a big leafy bundle of lettuce and dip it into a sweet tangy fish sauce ğŸ˜˜ Then embrace the explosion of crunch and savory flavor in one bite, itâ€™s so delicious! ğŸ¤¤ 

My verdict with this place, doesnâ€™t compare to momâ€™s Banh Xeo. However, their version is still delightful but not the best I had ğŸ‘Œ Itâ€™s on the lighter side in flavor, maybe good for westerner to train their taste buds. ğŸ‘… #vietnamesefood #saigon

â€œUnlike Earth, the atmosphere of Mars is dominated by micron-size dust aerosols, and the sky during sunset takes on a bluish glow.â€ From: Applied Optics Vol. 53, Issue 9

Iâ€™ve been experimenting with the public domain images available on the NASA website. What you see here are constructed entirely from that source. Itâ€™s been strange, and wasnâ€™t until I found the article referenced above that I realized why. The light on Mars is â€˜weirdâ€™ because the atmosphere is different. Go figure.

As I worked, the project became as much about understanding this unique light as playing with Martin landforms. The images here explore a few ways to bridge a blue light source - with golden/orange scattering, across a few different angles and times of day in a variety of atmospheric dust. Itâ€™s definitely not accurate, and surely exaggerated. (Check out the article, lots of math above my ability) The science was simply a point of departure for experimentation. The main gist i held in mind, is that blue can transition through purple & red or green & yellow to get to orange. Just walk your way around a color wheel. Fun. After a month tho, Iâ€™m ready to go look at some foliage.

The clam diggers. A rainy day conversation with, James Abbott McNeill Whistler, and Idris Khan, perhaps a drop in by Todd Hido...

I donâ€™t know any of these cats. Idris and Todd are making powerful work today, but James was born in 1834, so it might be a challenge for us to get together. But, thatâ€™s the cool thing about art. We can dialogue with anyone throughout time.

This one finds me curious about their feelings on substance vs style. Inspiration vs appropriation. The relationship between how we make something, and why. 

Idris created a seminal series that appropriated the work of Bernd and Hilla Becher, with (it appears) the intent of adding meaning. Toddâ€™s style is highly copied by other contemporary photographers, who arguably donâ€™t add additional meaning. And James was a big proponent of art for aesthetics alone - meaning be damned (and fought over in lawsuits.) Of course his stance was taken in an age when images were relatively rare and filled with allegory, which to him might have made this fight feel - quite meaningful. ğŸ™ƒ
This was too good not to shoot something extra.

Eagle Pass, TX : A US Border Patrol agent holds a wailing child after helping several adolescent migrants - those already on US territory - cross large swaths of razor concertina wire set out by the TX National Guard. The wire is meant to dissuade and keep migrants from coming ashore and claiming asylum, a right enshrined in current American law.

#politics #immigration #migrants #eaglepasstx #migration

More hopeful migrants cross the Rio Grande River towards Eagle Pass, TX. All hoping for a better life and more opportunities in the US. But many face the harsh realities of an overloaded and broken American immigration system. Many apply for asylum before crossing, but often find themselves the victims of criminals, or the lack of adequate housing forces them into a desperate decision to cross into the US. 

#politics #immigration #eaglepasstx #photojournalism #reportage #migrants

Eagle Pass, TX - A migrant mother and daughter embrace after making it across the Rio Grande and past a riverbank lined with razor wire and TX National Guard. 
With all the political rhetoric these days - many forget these are actual human beings struggling to find a better life. 

#photojournalism #reportage #politics #eaglepass #migration #immigration

One of the other projects I did in Yemen were these portraits of Yemenis that played into the assignment I was working on, along with people I met during wanderings around different cities. 

This project could be the indirect reason I was detailed when I came back to the US. 

The second image is a portrait of the leader (at the time) of Al Qaedaâ€™s political wing in Yemen.  He really liked the image and asked if I could send it to him. We used the old â€œbumpâ€ iPhone app to exchange the image. And Iâ€™m pretty sure my phone was compromised from there on out. 

To make matters worse - we were meeting in a large cafe for safety - the next interview subject came in to meet the writer and I a bit early. The third image is a portrait of the last Rabbi in Yemen. Obviously the head of Al Qaeda and the Rabbi kept their affiliations on the DL - so neither knew who each one was. They actually exchanged pleasant greetings and traded places - as the rabbi stayed for an interview and portrait.

The fourth image is a former Guantanamo prisoner who was returned to Yemen after serving a few years in the prison and found either not guilty or not worth US efforts to interrogate him. He was unemployed and trying to figure out how to continue a life cut short. 

#portrait #photojournalism #reportage #onassignment #documentary #yemen #tintype

c.@legolandcalifornia hotel. â€” itâ€™s heaven for a family with children, kids LOVE it! Parents, too! ğŸ˜ƒ

Each moment becoming an unforgettable experience:Â 
1. Cerulean Tower Tokyu Hotel: A luxurious stay in Shibuya offering mesmerising cityscape views, transforming into a captivating tapestry of lights at night.Â 
2. Mount Mitake Mystical Forest: Just a short trip from Tokyo, Mount Mitake enchanted with mist-shrouded ancient cedars and the soothing sounds of nature.Â 
3. Mitake Sanso Shukubo Retreat: The traditional temple lodge provided an authentic escape, immersing in cultural heritage.Â 
4. KabukichoTheater: Stepping into Shinjukuâ€™s Kabukicho Theater was a journey into Japanâ€™s theatrical tradition, bridging the gap between modernity and history.Â 
5. Sunset over Mount Fuji unveiled a breathtaking sunset, casting a warm glow over the iconic silhouette of Mount Fuji. 
Â #TokyoTokyo #Japan

Golden moments exploring Tokyoâ€¦âœ¨
Amidst the vibrant city lights, there's a magical moment that unfolds as dawn breaks over Tokyo, watching the sunrise over the skyline from our Cerulean Tower Tokyu Hotel. On our last day we ventured to Kabukicho Theater, this vibrant district of Shinjuku is home to this iconic venue, where Kabuki performances adapted in modern styles unfold. Stepping into the theater is like stepping back in time, as the elaborate costumes, mesmerising makeup, and captivating storytelling transport you to the world of Japanese theater.
#tokyotokyo #tokyotokyooldmeetsnew #japan

Embrace the beauty of autumn in Tokyo with these unforgettable experiences:Â 

1. Mount Mitake: A hidden gem just over an hour from Tokyo, where ancient cedars and vibrant foliage paint the mountainside.
2. Hatonosu Valley Walk: Immerse yourself in nature's golden embrace with a stroll through the scenic Â HatonosuHatanosu Valley.Â 
3. Lake Shiromaru Canoeing Experience: Glide through the serene waters, surrounded by the breathtaking colours of fall.
4. Mitake Sanso Shukubo Experience: Stay in a traditional temple lodge, experiencing the tranquility of Mount Mitake overnight.Â

#TokyoTokyo #Japan

Just over an hour by train Mount Mitake is my favourite hidden gem and most surprisingly this is still part of Tokyoâ€¦ âœ¨ As autumn paints the landscape, there's a particular magic that unfolds when you combine the vibrant colours of fall with the tranquil experience of canoeing on Lake Shiromaru. The turquoise blue and green of the lake reflects the kaleidoscope of autumn coloursâ€”shades of fiery red, golden yellow, and burnt orange.Â #TokyoTokyo #Japan #MountMitake

The glow from aboveâ€¦âœ¨ As I reached the top of the enchanting Mount Mitake, the panoramic view of Mount Fuji unfolded before me. The sprawling metropolis of Tokyo lay in the distance, its iconic skyline blending with the horizon. Lush mountainside forests carpeted the landscape, their deep green and orange hues contrasting with the sleek architecture of Tokyo. #TokyoTokyo #Japan #MountMitake

- Moderating the frequency of hair washing to once a week.

- Incorporating in-salon professional treatments for relaxation and rejuvenation.
- Reducing the use of heat styling tools.
- Investing in a silk pillow for added care and comfort. #HairRevivalJourney #GratefulForExperts

El Camino Real de Baja California runs from Tijuana to Loreto, Mexico. Many are familiar with El Camino Real of Alta California (modern-day California), which is lined with bells and passes through cities like Los Angeles and San Francisco. The old road in Baja has been forgotten, even though it played a massive role in the development of the whole region. The roads were originally trails made by the indigenous communities of the region, whose people were killed, died from diseases and were used as slave labor to build the road by the Spanish.
 
 
-Felipe Villa Poblano, who has lived next to the Mission Santa Gertrudis for 26 years, has a small store and looks after the mission. Mission Santa Gertrudis was established in 1751 by the Jesuits to convert CochimÃ­ Indians.

Here are some tips for budget friendly trips:

âœˆï¸ *Avoid Peak Season* Not only a way to avoid crowds but youâ€™ll usually be able to get a better deal. You might not be able to guarantee nice weather, but your destination will at least be a lot less crowded!

âœˆï¸ *Book in Advance* Prices will often go up as time gets closer to your trip. Booking train journeys, accommodation & flights ahead of time guarantees you wonâ€™t get stung by a last minute expensive prices.

âœˆï¸ *Purchase travel insurance* It may seem like an additional upfront expense, but itâ€™s best to view it as an investment thatÂ can help you save money during medical emergencies and unexpected cancellations.

âœˆï¸ *Using public transportation* during your trip can save you money.Â The bus or whatever the local transport of the country youâ€™re visiting is always cheaperÂ than a taxi or an Uber. Walking is my personal favourite way to discover anywhere! 

âœˆï¸ *Choose cheaper accommodation* Hotels can be quite expensive so choose a more budget friendly stay such as a hostel or apartment. 

âœˆï¸ *Pack light* to avoid baggage expenses. Airports impose pretty hefty extra fees for large and heavy baggage. Also pack well, write lists (I have a notes app full of themğŸ˜„) so you donâ€™t forget anything and have to buy duplicate things abroad that you already have at home. 

âœˆï¸ *Eat Local* Stay away from the touristy areas. You can often see places that are popular with the locals, they serve cheaper food and youâ€™ll get a much more authentic look into the cuisine of that country!

âœˆï¸ *Save up frequent flyerÂ miles* Itâ€™s definitely worth joining a frequent flyer program & racking up those miles/points. Over time they really add up and can get you discounted flights and upgrades!

âœˆï¸ *Bring your own food*Â Whenever possible, stock up on sandwiches and snacks for the trip. Avoid buying meals at the airport/on the road/hotel minibar which are Â£Â£Â£.

âœˆï¸ *Skip overpriced Tours* Explore yourself, with the information available online, itâ€™s simple and easy to conduct your own tour for free rather than paying for a guide.

..and if you spend less on one adventure, you have money to spend on another! ğŸ¥³
