Scotland Fix of the Day: Scottish landscapes loom large in my photographic world so I'm very pleased to share that The Independent Photographer has a new profile about me that shines quite a bit of light into my photography and background. All credit to Josh Bright for pulling it together so brilliantly. (He's more generous than I deserve but I'm not arguing.) Most of all I appreciate the chance to talk about why landscapes are so important to me, why they speak not just to geography but also to our hearts and souls. Looking for Scotland: If Scotland is on your travel list for 2024 let me offer my Top Ten Things To Do. Everybody has their list of Best Castles and Must See sites. With my list I hope to suggest ways of seeing Scotland that might get you away from checklist travel and into another realm. Here goes:

1. Visit a castle (of course) but let the history wash over you. Do a deep dive into its turns of fortune, failures and disasters. Eilean Donan is a good one. 
2. Find a Highland Games in some remote glen. Take part in the gathering, however you can. If they have a visitors tug of war, pull for all your worth. If they have a dance, dance.
3. Find a remote country house hotel that knows Scottish hospitality. Let them spoil you for a couple of days. Iâ€™d hole up in Eilean Iarmain on Skye.
4. Sit amongst the puffins. Be patient.
5. Find someplace with stonking, bloody Scottish history. Iona is just one of many, but itâ€™s got Celtic Saints, Viking raids and Macbeth in the graveyard.
6. Visit a coastal village with one pub. Buy somebody a pint. Pennan is a likely choice, but watch Local Hero before you go. 
7. Be picky about which distillery you visit. Avoid glitz. Strathisla is one of those ancient distilleries that still looks oldâ€¦because it actually is. 
8. Lie down in the heather and take a nap.
9. Find a red phone booth that is still working and call someone. 
10. Spend an evening at a stone circle in the moonlight. The Stones of Stenness in Orkney is a good bet. 

Thereâ€™s more, of course, and much I have yet to see myself. Before you go buy Scotland, the Best by Peter Irvine, the hands down best Scottish guide book. Relish its handpicked lists of treasures and oddities long before you go.

Scotland Fix: Few settings seem so right for listening to the Great Highland Bagpipe as a rainy day at the head of Loch Shiel. Here at the Glennfinnan Gathering the piping competition takes place down by the shore, the very place where Bonnie Prince Charlie came ashore on his ill-fated Jacobite mission. The bagpiper is concentrating as he plays the piobaireachd, the ancient classical music set down in the mists of lost history and still revered today. He paces around the platform, "slowly, but not too slowly" in precise, measured steps. The judge stares into the distance, careful to not let the magnificent, romantic scene cloud his judgement. Judge and piper share a quest to keep alive something that could die without them. For a bagpiper, I think, this is Carnegie Hall.

Scottish landscapes reveal much of Scottish character, especially out in the islands where the Atlantic storms do battle with the land. So it was that a sodden pony on North Uist taught me a lesson on rainy day. 

It sidled up next to my car, refusing to go stand a ways off in the moor to make a pretty picture for me, a picture that did not involve a soggy mane. But then it dawned on me: the soggy mane was the picture, a pattern of ringlets redolent of Celtic symbols seen here a thousand years ago. 

Sometimes Iâ€™m afraid that the land is trying to tell me something and I wonâ€™t get it. Over fifty years of photography that has happened to me plenty of times. Itâ€™s daunting to think that you can be standing in front of something wonderful, and just not be able to see it. So I thank this pony for its patience. It stood there long enough for me to get it. 

Had any stories of revelations that got away?  Comments welcome.

By the way, locals call it the Hairy Loch for good reason owing to these grasses. Itâ€™s often calm and a prime photo stop on the Isle of Skye â€” if the midgies are held at bay. 

Lots of legends attached to this place, that St. Columba drove away an evil spirit in 570 AD (he did that a lot), that a shape shifting water horse (Kelpie) took up residence and in the form of a handsome young man lured maidens to their death in the loch, even that a Norwegian princess named Saucy Mary is buried on top of Beinn na Caillich back there.

Scotland Fix of the Day: Getting away sometimes leads to finding yourself. Thatâ€™s one attraction of the Scottish landscape for me, the chance to truly be alone with the place, unfettered with expectations, content to accept the character of the land (and of yourself) as it is. Here are a few places that have evoked that sense for me. 

1. The long one-track road on Jura that ends after 17 miles just south of the house where George Orwell wrote 1984.
2. Eilean na Moine, the wee island in Loch Eilt that became most known as the site of Dumbledoreâ€™s grave. Few other island seem to stand so alone. 
3. The moors of Assynt stretch off into vast openness when seen from atop Sgorr Tuath, or from Stac Pollaidh across the way. 
4. Evening at the Ring of Brodgar in Orkney can be sublime, the stones â€” and endless time â€” your only companions. Iâ€™ve often felt comforted here.

Forgotten Story: The Culture of Sugar

On 14 October 1492, Christopher Columbus touched land after leaving Spain on the islands known as GuanahanÃ­, today called the Bahamas. Taking slaves (he was a slave owner, too), two months later, on 5 December, he landed on the island of Taino. In a typical conquering manner, renaming it La Isla EspaÃ±ola, or The Spanish Island, later called Hispaniola. Today, Hispaniola is dividedâ€”the Dominican Republic on the east and Haiti on the west.

Knowing the culture of the Caribbean well, for the @NatGeo story, The Culture of Sugar (read the first sugar caption in my IG), Haiti is uniqueâ€¦in Haitian Vodou, sugar is of spiritual importance.

Vodou came with slaves forced from central and western Africa to Haiti shortly after Columbus. This most special, beautifully unique form of spirituality is often misunderstood and interwoven in Haitian culture.

@RegineParicia, a specialist in Haitian culture, knew of a Rada lwa ceremony 30 km (about 20 mi) from Port-au-Prince. Traveling with filmmaker @AnkaVision (Anka was creating a NatGeo TV Amazing Photos documentary for this chapter on sugar), we were welcomed by the community of Dumilseau Village in La Plaine into rituals, healings, and trance like nowhere else on earth.

Why sugar and vodou?

Sugar is essential in Haitian Vodouâ€“many spirits require sweet, sugary substances.

Intricate patterns of religious symbols, called Veveâ€™s, are created on the earth using flour, ground coffee, and offerings of sugarâ€¦sodas, and Barbancourt rum, made from sugarcane.

A table-like altar was created for the Cra Bi Nay Ceremony to honor the spirit Bossou, adorned with orange sodas, Coca-Cola, and candies.

Before a cow was sacrificed, many went into a trance, pouring sugary rum over their bodies and making offerings of sugar to the spirits. Others were healed with soda. Music was hypnotic, a reminder of the rhythms I heard as a child living in the Bahamas playing with my classmates at their homes, some of whom were of Haitian descent.

A short film in this album shares this beautiful intensity where sugar and spirituality merge.

Forgotten Story: The Culture of Sugar.

The history of sugar is bitter by dark moments of our human ego and desires for control.

For thousands of years, this sweetness was cultivated from the grass known as sugarcane, moving from Oceania by trade.

In colder climates of Europe where sugarcane would not grow, the demand for sugar during a time when such delights were rare, and spreading Colonization, the spice wars began in the 15th century for flavor-filled items like nutmeg, cinnamon, and yes, sugar. By the 18th century, most sugar was obtained from the West Indies.

During the Napoleonic Wars, sugar supplies were cut off by the English blockade of continental Europe.

To make up for this loss, Napoleon Bonaparte encouraged the growing of beetsâ€¦in the 17th century, a German chemist discovered white and red beetroot contained sucrose, able to extract sugar.

After gaining a presence in France, the introduction of sugar beet production in the United States was first established, a short drive from where I live to North Hampton, MAâ€”by 1883, ceasing operation.

It wasnâ€™t until seeds arrived in North Dakota from Michigan in the late 1800s that sugar from beets became viable. With heavy labor done by German and Russian immigrants who moved to North Dakota for jobs, the surrounding areas of Fargo became the epicenter of sugar production in the United States.

In 1899, American Crystal Sugar was founded, and so began the most significant crop production of sugar beets in North America, along the Red River Valley in North Dakota.

From the @NatGeo story, The Culture of Sugar, which was never published (read why in the caption in my first post of this story), sharing with you the mesmerizing movement of how nearly all white processed sugar at American Crystal Sugar is produced for US consumption.

To understand the enormity of our desire for sweetness, the images inside the storage silo represent 35 million tonnes, or the equivalent of 7 million 2.3 kg (5 lb) bags of sugar.

A short film is in this album on the mysterious machines that create this sugar desire.

Forgotten Story: The Culture of Sugar.

Once a rare spice, every genus of sugar originates east of the Wallace Line in Papua New Guinea.

Beginning in around 4 C.E., sugar moved from Oceania through trade often connected to conflict and slaveryâ€¦at that time in history, nowhere else on earth had or grew sugar.

For the unpublished @NatGeo story, The Culture of Sugar, these crystals are culturally unimaginable in PNG culture.

Unaware of what to expect, my contact was Father Paul Kanda, a Papuan Catholic priest who told me, â€œJohn, just come, I will show you.â€

After four days of travel by propeller plane and trucks to reach the highlands of Enga Province, there was a wedding.

Father Kanda drove us to a hillside where I met William Waikenda, a kamongo or tribal leader, preparing for the Yari ceremony in Wapai Village. He would lead the Yole Maingi (bride prize) ceremony in a few hours, uniting a woman and man before a Christian marriage.

Insects swarmed everywhere, drawn to the sweetness of sugarcane leaning against a tree.

Down the hill, I found the groom, 24-year-old Samuel Tembe, skipping along a pathway through a gorgeous landscape of greenness to meet his bride.

At a clearing in Wapai was 20-year-old Janet Sani and her family; Samuel took his place next to his future wife and immediately began the Yole Maingi (bride prize).

Why sugar?

Giving and eating raw sugarcane is essential; the bridge or conduit to unite two tribes creates harmony between the bride and groomâ€™s tribes. A practice for thousands of years in the Highlands of Papua New Guinea.

When leaving, William Waikenda insisted I take three sugarcane sticks. Unkind to say no, confused about what to do with this long gift, I rested three canes out of the truck window, enjoying a few bites. Later, I gave Father Kanda the rest of the massive poles.

Sharing more stories of the fascination with sugar from Papua New Guinea in the coming daysâ€¦. The Yole Maingi ceremony only touches the unimaginable sugar culture, the roots of this now common sweetener.

Also included is a short video.

With India having the unpleasant recognition as the second highest rate of diabetes (China is first, both due to large populations) and wanting to return to my favorite spiritual city, Varanasi (Banaras, also known as Kashi), I did the usual movement of learning, while not knowing or expecting anything. This was when I met Ram Ji, squatting like a guru upon a small wooden stool along Godowlia Street, cleaning teeth, making dentures, and catering to the dental needs of the poorest of the poor. He didnâ€™t know his age, guessing at the time he was 85.

Forgotten Story: Going through the archive for an exhibition opening later this year in Tbilisi, I remembered a story that never was published in @NatGeo: The Culture of Sugar.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
For over a year, I explored how this common sweet substance has a captivating, often lengthy, dark history.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Why did the sugar story not publish?
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
National Geographic had commissioned a new writer. Midway through the reporting, they rejected the manuscript. Such unfortunateness was a giftâ€¦I could write the visual narrative, unconstrained in complete curiosity.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Around midway through, I was introduced to a new writer, sharing what I had been creating. After a few months, this writerâ€™s manuscript was also rejected.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
When the photography was completed â€” Oceania, South and Southeast Asia, the Caribbean, and the United States â€” the magazine commissioned a third writer, Rich Cohen, author of Sweet and Low: A Family Story, a memoir about the creation of the artificial sweetener in the pink packet invented by Benjamin Eisenstadt, Cohenâ€™s grandfather.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
National Geographic accepted Richâ€™s manuscript, but this time, the text had nothing to do with the culture of sugar: the story focused more on the health issues of sugar, not a global narrative on the culture of sugar.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
My good friend, @robertclarkphoto, was hired to photograph sugary foods in his studio, creating beautiful images to accompany Cohenâ€™s text.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
I was not upset at this unexpectedness. Life often shifts.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Will begin publishing this story here on the discovery of a forgotten photo essay on sugar.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Oh, hereâ€™s a touching to comeâ€¦Christopher Columbus didnâ€™t travel from Spain to discover an alleged â€œnew world.â€ (there were millions of fellow humans already there!).
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
He came to the western hemisphere looking for new places to cultivate sugar, a grass family species originating in Papua New Guinea.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
Caption: Laborers load sugarcane on a truck in Gambar field in Sumberasri village outside Blitar in East Java, Indonesia.

Today is the 11th year of Paul Salopekâ€™s walk around our world, the @outofedenwalk. Paul began this unimaginable journey on January 10, 2013, from Herto Buri, Ethiopia, returning to that day with walking partner Ahmed Elema in the Afar desert. I have learned so much and been inspired by Paul for over a decade. Walking together across two continents and 12 countries on this 24,000-mile odyssey, following in the footsteps of our ancestors on this @NatGeo project. Last year, I met up with Paul in northern China as we neared Beijing (that story will be published in National Geographic later this year). A few million more footprints to go, sending kindness, the fire of doing to my friend Paul and his many more million footprints to come as we walk towards North America, onward over the coming years through Central and South America, till reaching the tip of Argentina in Tierra del Fuego. Love you, Paul, seeing you soonâ€¦â¤ï¸âœ¨

No words can explain the uniqueness. An event of photography like I never before have hosted.

From 27 February through 13 March 2024, we return to my second home, Bali, for the most unimaginable storytelling workshop. 16 days on the Island of The Spirits during sacred events of Galungan, Kuningan, Melasti, and the profound day of Nyepi ~ the Day of Silence.

It has been decades since these most important days occurred so close to one another, each expressing profound moments during the most extended workshop Iâ€™ve ever hosted.

This intimate gathering will stretch your consciousness through awareness of long-form visual storytelling. Guide only ten photographers on creating an in-depth essay, like I create for National Geographic. In deepest giving to your narrative, your completed project should be ready for pitching to a magazine, even becoming a book or exhibition.

Only two spaces remain until we are full.

As always, we are offering a special workshop fee for early registration and even more discounts for those returning from our Workshop Family.

Complete details about this unimaginable event are at the link in my Instagram bio or by visiting stanmeyer.com

I suggest registering as soon as possible, as these two last spaces will fill quickly.

In early 2024, I look forward to lifting you through the meditation of long narrative visual storytelling during this unfathomably unique period of Indonesian culture in Bali.

John

Iâ€™ve always followed the traditional thinking, honed into me by #NatGeo, that a photo should be as realistic as possible, without major edits or removing unwanted objects. For journalism, that works, but it leaves little room for more extreme artistic expression in post production. Itâ€™s taken me a long time to free my mind enough to explore that other side, which seems strange to me now as I write that because I consider myself a pretty creative and out of the box thinker. I guess that Iâ€™ve been so focused on the perfect/real photo that I never let myself think about what a photo could be if I completely break free of those chains. So Iâ€™ve been playing around with more extreme photoshop editing on a couple of images to see where it takes me, and itâ€™s been really fun and freeing. Iâ€™d never call these real photos, but they are based on actual images Iâ€™ve taken (Iâ€™ve included both the edited and unedited images in two examples). What do you think of the heavily edited surreal photos? Too much? Or shall I continue down this path?
Lone twiga (giraffe) ambling at sunset on the great open expanse of Kenyaâ€™s Maasai Mara. #kenya #safari

Eye to Eye. 

Itâ€™s tough to watch any animal die. Our human instinct is to look away and feel a sense of shame/guilt for even wanting the hunt to happen in the first place. Itâ€™s a normal and perfectly fine reaction. But life in the Maasai Mara is not easy, and lions must kill to survive. Weâ€™ve lost over 90% of the lion population in the last 50+ years. Lions are in serious trouble, and I canâ€™t imagine a world in which we canâ€™t see them in the wild. So I try to bear witness, without wishing a kill to happen but also not looking away when it does.

On this particular morning, these two male lions ambushed a rather large herd of buffalo, and managed to separate this one from the group. It was over rather quickly, as these two brothers are expert hunters and together thereâ€™s not much that they canâ€™t take down. Thatâ€™s more than I can say for other kills Iâ€™ve witnessed. 

Such is the tug and pull (figuratively, and in this case, quite literally too) of life on the Mara. #kenya #safari

The word â€œlemurâ€Â (/ËˆliËmÉ™r/), from the Latin wordÂ â€œlemuresâ€, means â€œghostâ€ or â€œspirit.â€ Itâ€™s not hard to understand the root of this name when you gaze upon Randrianasoloâ€™s sportive lemur (Lepilemur randrianasoloi),Â also known as the Bemaraha sportive lemur. They certainly have a spooky gaze. Local legend says that this sportive lemur can cast spells with its intense gaze. I accidentally disturbed this little arboreal night lemur while walking in the daytime (its bedtime) through the dry, deciduous forests within the Tsingy de Bemaraha National Park in western Madagascar. Iâ€™m not sure, but it may have placed a curse on me. Fair warning: zooming in MAY cause nightmares. #madagascar #lemur

Unlike most of the world, endemicity is the norm in Madagascar. I eventually learned that I had to stop asking if something I was seeing was endemic because the answer was always â€œyesâ€. It became quite comical. The same could be true for whether a species was threatened or not. It was almost always threatened, sadly to say. 

I have always loved chameleons and was excited to see some in the wilds of Madagascar. Hereâ€™s another endemic and threatened species, a baby short-horned chameleon (Calumma brevicorne) that I photographed outside of the Andasibe-Mantadia National Park on the eastern side of the island. I like the colors of this photo, along with the precarious perch he/she was hanging on to.  #madagascar #chameleon

Howâ€™s it hangin?

A Verreaux's sifaka (Propithecus verreauxi), or the white sifaka (a lemur in the Indriidae family), takes a break from foraging to see where her friends have scurried off to. Rest assured, they are not far. #madagascar #lemur

With pointy white and furry ears, orange eyes (that reflect Berentyâ€™s red soil), a long and beautiful tail, and a seemingly endless desire for play and socialization, the ring-tailed lemur (Lemur catta) is a primate that holds a special place in my heart. I had the pleasure of spending several days photographing them in Madagascarâ€™s Berenty Private Reserve, and I simply could not get enough of their antics. I apologize ahead of time for the lemur photo dump that is sure to follow. 

The most conspicuous feature of the ring-tailed lemur is its long tail that is adorned with 26 black and white alternating rings, the first of which is always white and the last one (the tip of the tail) is always black. The tail is used for balance and communication, not for grabbing (it is not prehensile). 

The ring-tailed #lemur is both endemic to #Madagascar and endangered, facing the loss of their forest habitat as a result of stock overgrazing, field burning/clearing, as well as tree-cutting for making charcoal. National parks and private reserves (such as Berenty) play an important role in the survival of species like these.

ğŸ’ To get the best shape and maximum weight, the planner has to accurately assume the colour of the final polished diamonds; any mistake in assumption results in a different outcome of the colour.

ğŸ’ The cutter has to be mindful of the possibility of generating too much heat during the initial laser-cutting process, which can alter the gemâ€™s hue.

ğŸ’ The bruiter during the bruiting stage also takes care to maintain the appropriate thickness of the girdle, as the gemâ€™s hue could change due to a thicker girdle.

ğŸ’ The polisherâ€™s keen eyes and understanding of the twins are used to achieve perfectly identical proportions.

Jump through, straight legs sit down. This is a phrase that you will hear over and over again and every single Ashtanga Yoga class. If you keep practicing, you may even hear this phrase in your dreams.

Learning to jump through holds so much information about inversions, strength, mental, focus, and surrender. You canâ€™t rush the process of building the foundational strength in order to learn the lesson of jumping through. You can, however, focus on the step-by-step technique that will eventually lead you there. 

I remember when I first started practicing how frustrating it was that I couldnâ€™t do this movement. Now, more than 20 years later, I still think there are many ways to refine the movement and get stronger. Whatâ€™s important to me is not the performative aspect, but the connection of breath, awareness and mental focus. This is the essence of the flow that happens when our mind and body are completely harmonized.

Now Iâ€™m missing hearing my teacher tell us all to jump through as I unroll my mat on my own.

We bear the fruits of every action we take. Karma is a universal law of action. Both the intended and unintended consequences of our actions rest on our shoulders. I donâ€™t see this a zero sum game of winners and losers or some harsh deity that issues judgement. Instead, every experience is all about learning, growing and evolving. 

An action we take with the best intentions reverberates for lifetimes with both positive and negative impact on our lives and the lives of those around us. We can be working through the residual impact for as long as need in order to integrate the spiritual lesson. Repetition isnâ€™t always due to failure. Sometimes itâ€™s about seeing another person or reaching a deeper layer. 

Once we are strong enough to see ourselves clearly, we are ready to really go through the process of spiritual awakening. Everything we do in three practice prepares us for increasingly deeper levels of self-realization. We canâ€™t rush. We can only go at our own pace and trust that what is meant to happen will happen when itâ€™s meant to happen.

In 2007 I was hired by @timberland to do a series of ads where they wanted a sense of motion conveyed, without using motion blur. I pitched them on using light streaks to show motion paths, by strapping headlamps to hands and wrists of athletes. This one here was with my friend @joekinder climbing on a bridge near Manitou Springs, CO. To capture this frame we determined the end point of the frame where my flash would fire and freeze the action, which is essentially what frame 3 is. Joe started at the base, and climbed to that point with headlamps on wrists and feet, while I left the shutter open, firing the flash once he hit our established end point. The total exposure time was 94 seconds, leaving behind his light path in a fun way, all done entirely in camera.

Itâ€™s been a long time since Iâ€™ve introduced myself on Instagram. I donâ€™t think I ever did. One day, 12 years ago, I was here, and that was that. But Iâ€™ve recently committed to going back to basics in my life and thought that was worth further explanation here.

In my time on Instagram, Iâ€™ve been a chef turned professional Instagrammer and travel photographer. Iâ€™ve become a consultant, campaign manager and public speaker. Iâ€™ve created an online photography course, co-founded an event and run photography tours to Zimbabwe. Iâ€™ve been to all seven continents with paid work, and during Covid, I became a business coach and the Managing Director of a seven-figure startup. Then I gave it all away.

As my successes piled up, I realised that not only did I now know who I was without them, I didnâ€™t believe that I was enough without them either.

2022 became the year of undoing. I undid my business, stopped chasing the money and adulation, stopped creating and gave myself space to figure out who I am underneath it all. Not only did I find out, but I learned to love myself without any of it.

As I continue to sit into my power, embrace motherhood and find joy in the everyday, I also feel a calling to share my journey. You can read my blogs, subscribe to my emails and turn on post notifications for my Instagram stories if you want to come along.

This is one of the most confronting images that I took in Borneo and, for me, this was one of the hardest things Iâ€™ve ever had to shoot. Afterwards I went back to my room and just cried and cried and I still cry to think about it now. Iâ€™ve seen pictures like this in the media and spared them a few minutes of sympathy before moving on with my life, but seeing this with my own eyes affected me fundamentally. These are the long term cages, for animals that have slipped through the cracks. Theyâ€™ve either been too big to handle or sick with contagious diseases that canâ€™t enter the main population. Some are just waiting until the resources are there to put them onto a pre release island, some canâ€™t get along with other orangutans, some have been broken by humans and some are in long term sanctuary and will never have freedom again. Small though these cages are they can cost up to $20,000 and the resources arenâ€™t there to replace them with better facilities, yet. Although I saw many happy endings for orangutans in Samboja and Nyaru Menteng, I also saw too many animals in these cages. Depressed and dejected, although some are angry still and rattle their cages and spit as you walk by. Itâ€™s the difficult job of the program director here to prioritize cases, move animals around the different facilities and decide which are eligible for release. With so many moving parts theyâ€™re doing a fine job with the resources they have. Please leave a like and comment, even if you donâ€™t â€˜likeâ€™ the situation. I notice how much I struggle to honour low-energy days. I want to DO things. I get into all kinds of â€œstoriesâ€ about what it means about me if Iâ€™m not productive.

Whoa. What a weekend! This weekend, I had not one but two kids' birthday parties to attend. Donâ€™t get me wrong, I LOVE them. The party food, the cake, the nostalgia and, of course, the excitement on my kid's faces. Kids parties are great.

Theyâ€™re also very, very, very stimulating! And this weekend, I made the rookie error of putting off my journaling and beach visit until afterwards, meaning I was going into each party with my cup empty.

By yesterday afternoon, I was in struggle town. I was in a functional freeze state - disassociating and reaching for the phone for some mindless scrolling. I was highly emotional, very overwhelmed and still highly stimulated. I recognised the state and needed to make decisions to allow me to process and regulate.

I struggled to fall asleep after it all, physically feeling my body twitch as I came down. Itâ€™s a funny thing to know your own limits and still push past them because you donâ€™t want to miss out. The good news is that Iâ€™m learning. Itâ€™s time to honour my capacity more.

Today, I wanted to ease back into work with some slow and creative tasks, including editing a small gallery of shots from a womenâ€™s circle I attended two weeks ago.

Itâ€™s not an easy thing for me to admit that Iâ€™m not superwoman, for me to know and honour my limits. Although I CAN do a lot, I donâ€™t want to do a lot if it doesnâ€™t feel good.

Yesterday afternoon, I didnâ€™t feel good. This afternoon, I felt very good. I allow the feeling to guide me. â¤ï¸

#womenscircle #followthefeeling #emotionalregulation #nervoussystemregulation #fomo #surrender #superwoman #honourmyself

I had an interesting day yesterday. I was feeling low on energy and low on motivation. It was probably due to the New Moon, a time for introspection and letting go rather than hustling and DOING.

Naturally, I didnâ€™t feel like doing a thing and cancelled all the tasks Iâ€™d planned to work on in favour of doing some creative stuff at a snail's pace.

Even though Iâ€™d acknowledged the energy AND consciously chose to work with my (lower) energy, I still found myself getting into stories about it.

â€œItâ€™s only week one of being back at work, and youâ€™re already making excuses; this is why youâ€™re not going to make it.â€

â€œYouâ€™re feeling guilty for not doing much, and guilt is a low-vibration emotion. You know this, and yet you havenâ€™t even mastered shifting emotions.â€

â€œYou canâ€™t even get anything done. How will you do everything you want to do this year?â€

Blah, blah, blah.

But I kept choosing to sit with the discomfort and my inner knowing that we are simply not designed to hustle every single day. We are cyclical beings, and we work best when we allow for that.

This morning, I woke up, and all I wanted to do was create. I started writing like crazy, had an idea for a book and even took my camera down to the beach. This isnâ€™t the best shot, just the only shot I was able to edit briefly while I was watching the kids. I felt great!

Itâ€™s important to remember on the bad days that the good days are always coming. It will be my practice this year to sink more deeply into my downtime and continue to trust that I will get everything I want. I feel that so hard.

#photography #creativelife #creativeliving #newmoon #newmoonenergy #cyclical #surrender #trusttheuniverse

Iâ€™ve spent the last 18 months finding myself amongst the chaos of motherhood, exiting a business I loved and dismantling a set of beliefs that no longer served me.

During that time the biggest gift I gave myself was the gift of space. Space to reflect. Space to be curious about my life. Space to create without pressure. It was quite possibly the most impactful period of my life.

Amongst the many things I learned about myself, and life, is how to pay attention to the cycles. Because Iâ€™m not menstruating (still breastfeeding), I am more strongly impacted by the lunar cycle. My energy, emotions and moments of inspiration are all loosely following the cycles of the moon.

At first I didnâ€™t notice at all. Then it all seemed coincidental. But today, noticing that it is the new moon and feeling into my body and energy, I feel deeply aligned with it.

The New Moon is a time for reflection and planting seeds for the next cycle. It is not a time to be kicking goals. And I feel that HARD in my body.

To honour how I feel, and the cycles, Iâ€™m adjusting my day today to create more space and execute easier tasks. I can smash out the bulk work when my energy starts to build again.

If youâ€™re interested to know more about the cycles, Iâ€™ve been using @janehardwickecollings app â€˜Spinning Wheelsâ€™ and the @magic_of_i .

I know how woo woo this sounds. And I know we live in a society that doesnâ€™t let us believe we have the space to choose. But we do. Life has so much more meaning when we slow down, honour ourselves and trust that it will all get done.

#trust #theuniverse #newmoon #introspection #spinningwheels #thecycles #surrender2024

Last year I set a modest goal for myself to move my body two times a week.

One of those times was a half hour personal training session at my local private gym, a cost that I definitely could not afford at the time.

But health was high on my list of priorities and I partnered up with a friend to go halves in a 2-on-1 half hour session once a week. Itâ€™s not much. Half an hour.

But Iâ€™ll share something with you. That half an hour session, executed just 15 times, has been the catalyst for my new fitness goals for 2024.

Today was my last day doing personal training. For now at least. Iâ€™m joining a gym.

I sat on this decision for a long time because I have so little time to work, and I really didnâ€™t want my fitness to interfere with my work time. I am also still struggling with motivation, which was the reason why I needed a personal trainer in the first place.

Then, in an instant brainwave, I realised that I could find a gym with a crÃ¨che that runs group fitness classes and train in my parenting hours. (Dreamboat and I equally split parenting hours and working hours.)

Iâ€™ve tested it out and my kids LOVED the crÃ¨che! And I loved getting back on a spin bike again. I was grinning from ear to ear.

The point of my story is twofold. One is that you donâ€™t need to go from zero to a hundred. A year of gently adapting to exercise again created the momentum to set bigger goals this year. Iâ€™ve got my whole life to get my fitness on track. This year I hope to move my body four times a week, upping the ante on the intensity.

The second lesson is this, no matter what your personal circumstances are, there is a solution to your challenges. I have two babies and a business to restart in less than 25 hours a week. I also have zero motivation to exercise of my own accord. But I sat into the problem and found the solution. There is ALWAYS a solution.

Wish me luck on my fitness journey. â¤ï¸

Everywhere I look, I see people I love and admire talking about their yearly planning and sharing their processes.

I love planning. During the Phhnix days, I was a staunch defender of planning and saw first-hand how planning creates the structure to achieve any goal. Itâ€™s an infallible system.

I also find planning to be personally suffocating. I donâ€™t know if itâ€™s remnants of the business PTSD I have (joking, but also not), some other type of block or internal resistance, or if my intuition is telling me not to plan. Hear me out.

At the end of the day, the point of a plan is to achieve goals. A plan is a tool. Me? Iâ€™ve never had an issue executing tasks or achieving goals. On the contrary, my problem in business is usually taking on too much and spending my days in overwhelm.

Iâ€™m tired of trying to do things the way that other people do them. 2024 is a year for me to get really fucking curious about my working style and test out new ways. Ways that might or might not work, but will teach me at the very least.

So I wonâ€™t be planning this year, at least not beyond the simple note listing my goals and a running to-do list. Instead, Iâ€™ll be spending the majority of my working hours taking care of myself so that the work can flow like magic.

This looks like meditation, gym, beach and personal development during work time, and brief periods of intense focus to get through the actual work.

Iâ€™ll be sure to let you know how it works out for me. Iâ€™m a multi-dimensional being attempting to undo every story Iâ€™ve ever been told about success. If I canâ€™t FEEL good and be in my body, then I donâ€™t want it. No amount of success is worth my peace.

Ophelia

Lucinda Harmon Jackman,
4th wife of 7 to my namesake Levi Jackman, began her crossing of the American Great Plains on this day in 1849 in search of a new life free from persecution from the US government and religious zealots who declared her lifestyle as a Mormon an affront to god and society. Though historical accounts of Lucinda, my 3x Great Grandmother, are difficult to find in comparison to the documents detailing the life of her husband, the stirring personal parallels in our lives make it easy to imagine her as familiar. Because of her beliefs and non-traditional marriage, before trekking across the continent she was a societal outcast. She left the only world sheâ€™d ever known behind for a new chosen community, with whom she faced probable death in hopes of building a space where the next generation of their kind could feel safe. My heart finds a queerness in her story.
I donâ€™t know if the Lucinda of 1849 would be able to comprehend my queer existence today, but that doesnâ€™t diminish my desire to walk where she walked, reach through time and thank her for her precedent of pursuing love despite the sacrifices it would demand of her.

Thank you to @chloembower and @sammydigi for assisting on this project.

My Rainbow Baby journey ğŸ˜¢ğŸŒˆ

Many people donâ€™t know that Tyson is a rainbow babyğŸŒˆğŸ‘¶ğŸ½. For those that donâ€™t know what that means, itâ€™s that Tyson came after us miscarrying our baby before him. Itâ€™s taken a few years to decide if we wanted to share this, and just as long to feel comfortable taking about it. 

After hearing of struggles to get pregnant and miscarriages from people around us, we felt that we wanted to share so that others going through this feel less alone, as well as to give some hope. 

In early 2017, my husband and I got the wonderful news that we were going to have a baby, we were ecstatic and began planning for this blessed baby's arrival. I chatted with the baby regularly, and planned its nursery, planned our announcement etc. 

Then suddenly, just past 12 weeks, we lost our beloved baby. The pain, sadness and loneliness that goes along with this was unimaginable. Iâ€™m not sure why there is so much secrecy around a miscarriage here in North America, itâ€™s makes it so much worse. 

Not everything was â€˜evacuatedâ€™ when it happened so I was still carrying the baby after the miscarriage. When I asked my doctor what to do, she said I had to wait for it to pass naturally (which isnâ€™t true for everyone) ğŸ˜

For 9 months I still had all the hormones and the baby which made it so much harder to get past what happened. When I eventually found a new doctor, she took care of me and helped us to complete this chapter. We were finally able to mourn & have closure. When we were ready, we tried again ğŸ˜€

We are thankful that all the stars aligned to bring us the most special gift of our life, and the following year we got the news that we were pregnant again and Tyson was on his way. The main reason to share this story is to give hope to those out there going though some of the challenges of this. We send love to our little angel in heaven, and thanks for our little Tyson. 

 Sending hope, love & baby dust to anyone in needâ€¦ hugs xoxo â¤ï¸ğŸ™ğŸ¼ğŸŒˆ
